// notes/python.js — TOPIC_CONTENT entries for the python phase
Object.assign(TOPIC_CONTENT, {
  "python": "<main>\n  <h1>Python Programming Mastery</h1>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover \u2014 Python</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-vars\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Variables & Data Types</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Memory, mutability, type conversion</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-ops\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Operators</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Arithmetic, logical, bitwise, identity</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-control\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Control Flow</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">if/else, loops, pattern matching</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-functions\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Functions</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">args, kwargs, lambda, scope</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-ds\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Data Structures</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">list, tuple, set, dict, string</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-exceptions\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Exception Handling</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">try/except, custom exceptions</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-files\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">07</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">File Handling</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">txt, csv, json, parquet, pickle</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-modules\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">08</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Modules & Packages</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">imports, venv, pip, poetry</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-oop\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">09</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">OOP</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Classes, 4 pillars, SOLID, patterns</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-iterators\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">10</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Iterators & Generators</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">yield, lazy evaluation, memory</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-decorators\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">11</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Decorators</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">closures, wrappers, functools</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-context\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">12</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Context Managers</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">with, __enter__, __exit__</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-threads\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">13</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Multithreading</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">GIL, locks, thread pools</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-multiproc\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">14</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Multiprocessing</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">process pools, queues, shared memory</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-async\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">15</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Asyncio</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">event loop, coroutines, async/await</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-testing\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">16</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Testing & Debugging</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">pytest, mocking, profiling, logging</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n    <h2>Revision</h2>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>Mutable vs immutable:</strong> list/dict/set are mutable (change in place). int/str/tuple are immutable (new object on every change). Matters for function arguments and unexpected aliasing bugs.</li>\n      <li><strong>is vs ==:</strong> <code>==</code> checks value equality. <code>is</code> checks object identity (same memory address). <code>a = [1]; b = [1]; a == b</code> is True but <code>a is b</code> is False.</li>\n      <li><strong>*args / **kwargs:</strong> *args = variable positional args (tuple). **kwargs = variable keyword args (dict). Order: positional \u2192 *args \u2192 keyword \u2192 **kwargs.</li>\n      <li><strong>List vs tuple:</strong> list is mutable, slower, uses more memory. Tuple is immutable, faster, hashable (can be dict key). Use tuple for fixed data.</li>\n      <li><strong>dict hashing:</strong> dict keys must be hashable (immutable). Lookup is O(1) average. Lists can't be dict keys \u2014 they're mutable.</li>\n      <li><strong>Shallow vs deep copy:</strong> <code>b = a.copy()</code> copies the list but not nested objects. <code>copy.deepcopy(a)</code> copies everything recursively.</li>\n      <li><strong>Generator vs list:</strong> list computes all values at once (memory). Generator computes lazily \u2014 one value at a time. Use generators for large datasets.</li>\n      <li><strong>Decorator pattern:</strong> a function that takes a function and returns a modified function. Used for logging, timing, auth. <code>@decorator</code> is syntactic sugar for <code>func = decorator(func)</code>.</li>\n      <li><strong>GIL:</strong> Python's Global Interpreter Lock prevents true parallel thread execution. Threads work for I/O-bound tasks. Use multiprocessing for CPU-bound tasks.</li>\n      <li><strong>async/await:</strong> coroutines \u2014 functions that can pause and resume. Single-threaded concurrency. Best for I/O-bound tasks (API calls, DB queries) where waiting is the bottleneck.</li>\n      <li><strong>SOLID:</strong> Single responsibility, Open/closed, Liskov substitution, Interface segregation, Dependency inversion. Design principles for maintainable OOP code.</li>\n      <li><strong>MRO:</strong> Method Resolution Order \u2014 Python resolves which class's method to call in multiple inheritance using C3 linearisation. Check with <code>ClassName.__mro__</code>.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 1. VARIABLES \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-vars\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Variables & Data Types</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The mental model for Python variables</span>\n    <p>In Python, a variable is not a box that holds a value. It's a <strong>label</strong> (a name) that points to an object in memory. Two variables can point to the same object. When you do <code>b = a</code>, you're not copying \u2014 you're giving the same object a second label.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 160\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">Python variables are labels pointing to objects in memory</text>\n      <!-- a label -->\n      <rect x=\"30\" y=\"50\" width=\"60\" height=\"30\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"60\" y=\"70\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">a</text>\n      <!-- b label -->\n      <rect x=\"30\" y=\"100\" width=\"60\" height=\"30\" rx=\"6\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"60\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"12\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">b</text>\n      <!-- arrows -->\n      <path d=\"M90 65 L230 80\" stroke=\"#4F46E5\" stroke-width=\"2\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#pya)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M90 115 L230 95\" stroke=\"#4F46E5\" stroke-width=\"2\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#pya)\"/>\n      <!-- object in memory -->\n      <rect x=\"230\" y=\"60\" width=\"130\" height=\"55\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"295\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">[1, 2, 3]</text>\n      <text x=\"295\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">id: 0x7f3a...</text>\n      <!-- label annotation -->\n      <text x=\"390\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#5C6175\">a = [1, 2, 3]</text>\n      <text x=\"390\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#5C6175\">b = a   \u2190 same object!</text>\n      <text x=\"390\" y=\"98\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">a.append(4)</text>\n      <text x=\"390\" y=\"116\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">print(b)  \u2192 [1, 2, 3, 4]</text>\n      <text x=\"390\" y=\"134\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">b also changed \u2014 same list!</text>\n      <defs><marker id=\"pya\" markerWidth=\"7\" markerHeight=\"7\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L5,3 L0,6 Z\" fill=\"#4F46E5\"/></marker></defs>\n    </svg>\n    <figcaption>Both a and b point to the same list. Mutating via a also affects b. This surprises almost every beginner and causes real bugs in production.</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n\n  <h3>Mutable vs Immutable \u2014 the most important distinction</h3>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 150\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">Mutable = can change in place. Immutable = always creates a new object.</text>\n      <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"100\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Mutable (change in place)</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">list, dict, set, bytearray</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">a = [1,2]; b = a; a.append(3)</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">b is now [1,2,3] too \u2190 aliasing!</text>\n      <rect x=\"380\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"100\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">Immutable (new object)</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">int, float, str, tuple, frozenset</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">a = \"hello\"; b = a; a = a + \"!\"</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">b is still \"hello\" \u2190 safe!</text>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Memory and identity</span>\na = <span class=\"y\">42</span>\nb = <span class=\"y\">42</span>\nprint(a <span class=\"k\">is</span> b)    <span class=\"c\"># True \u2014 Python caches small integers (-5 to 256)</span>\nprint(id(a))      <span class=\"c\"># same memory address</span>\n\na = [<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>]\nb = a             <span class=\"c\"># both point to SAME list</span>\nb = a.copy()      <span class=\"c\"># shallow copy \u2014 new list, same inner objects</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> copy\nb = copy.deepcopy(a)  <span class=\"c\"># deep copy \u2014 new list AND new inner objects</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Type conversion</span>\nint(<span class=\"g\">\"42\"</span>)         <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 42</span>\nfloat(<span class=\"g\">\"3.14\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 3.14</span>\nstr(<span class=\"y\">42</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 \"42\"</span>\nlist((<span class=\"y\">1</span>,<span class=\"y\">2</span>,<span class=\"y\">3</span>))    <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [1, 2, 3]</span>\nbool(<span class=\"y\">0</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 False (falsy: 0, \"\", [], {}, None)</span>\nbool(<span class=\"g\">\"hello\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 True</span></div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The mutable default argument trap \u2014 classic Python bug</span>\n    <p>Never use a mutable object as a default argument. Default arguments are evaluated ONCE when the function is defined, not on each call.</p>\n    <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># WRONG \u2014 list is shared across all calls</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">append_to</span>(item, lst=[]):\n    lst.append(item)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> lst\n\nappend_to(<span class=\"y\">1</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [1]</span>\nappend_to(<span class=\"y\">2</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [1, 2]  \u2190 bug! shared state</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># CORRECT</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">append_to</span>(item, lst=<span class=\"k\">None</span>):\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> lst <span class=\"k\">is None</span>: lst = []\n    lst.append(item)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> lst</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 2. OPERATORS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-ops\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>Operators</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Arithmetic</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> + <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 13</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> - <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 7</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> * <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 30</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> / <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 3.333...  (always float)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> // <span class=\"y\">3</span>  <span class=\"c\"># 3          (floor division \u2014 always integer)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> % <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 1          (modulo \u2014 remainder)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> ** <span class=\"y\">3</span>  <span class=\"c\"># 1000       (exponentiation)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Comparison \u2014 all return bool</span>\n<span class=\"y\">3</span> == <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># True</span>\n<span class=\"y\">3</span> != <span class=\"y\">4</span>   <span class=\"c\"># True</span>\n<span class=\"y\">3</span> &lt; <span class=\"y\">4</span>    <span class=\"c\"># True</span>\n<span class=\"y\">3</span> &lt;= <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># True</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Logical</span>\n<span class=\"k\">True and False</span>   <span class=\"c\"># False</span>\n<span class=\"k\">True or False</span>    <span class=\"c\"># True</span>\n<span class=\"k\">not True</span>         <span class=\"c\"># False</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Short-circuit: \"and\" stops at first False, \"or\" stops at first True</span>\n<span class=\"y\">0</span> <span class=\"k\">or</span> <span class=\"g\">\"default\"</span>  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 \"default\"  (useful for fallback values)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> <span class=\"k\">and</span> <span class=\"g\">\"yes\"</span>     <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 \"yes\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Membership</span>\n<span class=\"y\">3</span> <span class=\"k\">in</span> [<span class=\"y\">1</span>,<span class=\"y\">2</span>,<span class=\"y\">3</span>]        <span class=\"c\"># True  \u2014 O(n) for list, O(1) for set/dict</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\"py\"</span> <span class=\"k\">in</span> <span class=\"g\">\"python\"</span>   <span class=\"c\"># True</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\"x\"</span> <span class=\"k\">not in</span> {<span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">1</span>} <span class=\"c\"># True \u2014 checks keys</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Identity</span>\na <span class=\"k\">is</span> b     <span class=\"c\"># same object? (same id())</span>\na <span class=\"k\">is not</span> b <span class=\"c\"># different object?</span>\na <span class=\"k\">is None</span>  <span class=\"c\"># preferred over a == None</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Bitwise (used in ML for flags, masks, hashing)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> &amp; <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 1   (AND:  0101 & 0011 = 0001)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> | <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 7   (OR:   0101 | 0011 = 0111)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> ^ <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 6   (XOR:  0101 ^ 0011 = 0110)</span>\n~<span class=\"y\">5</span>      <span class=\"c\"># -6  (NOT:  -(n+1))</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"y\">1</span>  <span class=\"c\"># 10  (left shift = multiply by 2)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> &gt;&gt; <span class=\"y\">1</span>  <span class=\"c\"># 2   (right shift = divide by 2)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Walrus operator := (Python 3.8+) \u2014 assign inside expression</span>\n<span class=\"k\">while</span> chunk := f.read(<span class=\"y\">1024</span>):\n    process(chunk)  <span class=\"c\"># reads and assigns in one expression</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 3. CONTROL FLOW \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-control\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Control Flow</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># if / elif / else</span>\nscore = <span class=\"y\">85</span>\n<span class=\"k\">if</span> score >= <span class=\"y\">90</span>:\n    grade = <span class=\"g\">\"A\"</span>\n<span class=\"k\">elif</span> score >= <span class=\"y\">80</span>:\n    grade = <span class=\"g\">\"B\"</span>\n<span class=\"k\">else</span>:\n    grade = <span class=\"g\">\"C\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Ternary (one-liner if/else)</span>\ngrade = <span class=\"g\">\"pass\"</span> <span class=\"k\">if</span> score >= <span class=\"y\">60</span> <span class=\"k\">else</span> <span class=\"g\">\"fail\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># for loop</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">5</span>):           <span class=\"c\"># 0, 1, 2, 3, 4</span>\n    print(i)\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> i, val <span class=\"k\">in</span> enumerate([<span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>,<span class=\"g\">\"b\"</span>,<span class=\"g\">\"c\"</span>]):  <span class=\"c\"># index + value</span>\n    print(i, val)            <span class=\"c\"># 0 a, 1 b, 2 c</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> k, v <span class=\"k\">in</span> {<span class=\"g\">\"x\"</span>:<span class=\"y\">1</span>,<span class=\"g\">\"y\"</span>:<span class=\"y\">2</span>}.items():\n    print(k, v)              <span class=\"c\"># dict iteration</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># while loop</span>\nn = <span class=\"y\">10</span>\n<span class=\"k\">while</span> n > <span class=\"y\">0</span>:\n    n -= <span class=\"y\">1</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># break / continue / else on loop</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">10</span>):\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> i == <span class=\"y\">5</span>: <span class=\"k\">break</span>     <span class=\"c\"># exit loop entirely</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> i % <span class=\"y\">2</span> == <span class=\"y\">0</span>: <span class=\"k\">continue</span>  <span class=\"c\"># skip to next iteration</span>\n<span class=\"k\">else</span>:\n    print(<span class=\"g\">\"loop finished without break\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># runs only if no break</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Pattern matching (Python 3.10+) \u2014 structural switch statement</span>\n<span class=\"k\">match</span> command:\n    <span class=\"k\">case</span> <span class=\"g\">\"quit\"</span>:\n        exit()\n    <span class=\"k\">case</span> <span class=\"g\">\"help\"</span> | <span class=\"g\">\"?\"</span>:\n        show_help()\n    <span class=\"k\">case</span> {<span class=\"g\">\"action\"</span>: action, <span class=\"g\">\"value\"</span>: value}:  <span class=\"c\"># match dict structure</span>\n        handle(action, value)\n    <span class=\"k\">case</span> _:\n        print(<span class=\"g\">\"unknown command\"</span>)              <span class=\"c\"># default</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 4. FUNCTIONS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-functions\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Functions</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Basic function</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">greet</span>(name: str, greeting: str = <span class=\"g\">\"Hello\"</span>) -> str:\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Docstring: greet a person. Type hints are documentation + tooling.\"\"\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> f<span class=\"g\">\"{greeting}, {name}!\"</span>\n\ngreet(<span class=\"g\">\"Aman\"</span>)                  <span class=\"c\"># positional</span>\ngreet(name=<span class=\"g\">\"Aman\"</span>, greeting=<span class=\"g\">\"Hey\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># keyword</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># *args \u2014 variable positional arguments (comes in as a tuple)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">total</span>(*args):\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> sum(args)\ntotal(<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">4</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 10</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># **kwargs \u2014 variable keyword arguments (comes in as a dict)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">config</span>(**kwargs):\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> k, v <span class=\"k\">in</span> kwargs.items():\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"{k}={v}\"</span>)\nconfig(lr=<span class=\"y\">0.001</span>, epochs=<span class=\"y\">10</span>, batch_size=<span class=\"y\">32</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Parameter order rule: positional \u2192 *args \u2192 keyword-only \u2192 **kwargs</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">f</span>(a, b, *args, key=<span class=\"g\">\"default\"</span>, **kwargs): ...\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Unpacking when calling</span>\nnums = [<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>]\nprint(*nums)              <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 1 2 3</span>\nsettings = {<span class=\"g\">\"lr\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">0.01</span>}\ntrain(**settings)         <span class=\"c\"># same as train(lr=0.01)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Lambda \u2014 anonymous single-expression function</span>\nsquare = <span class=\"k\">lambda</span> x: x ** <span class=\"y\">2</span>\nsorted_data = sorted(data, key=<span class=\"k\">lambda</span> x: x[<span class=\"g\">\"score\"</span>], reverse=<span class=\"k\">True</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Scope \u2014 LEGB rule (Local \u2192 Enclosing \u2192 Global \u2192 Built-in)</span>\nx = <span class=\"g\">\"global\"</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">outer</span>():\n    x = <span class=\"g\">\"enclosing\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">inner</span>():\n        <span class=\"k\">nonlocal</span> x       <span class=\"c\"># modify enclosing scope variable</span>\n        x = <span class=\"g\">\"inner\"</span>\n    inner()\n    print(x)             <span class=\"c\"># \"inner\"\n\n# global keyword \u2014 modify global from inside function</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">reset</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">global</span> x\n    x = <span class=\"g\">\"reset\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Recursion \u2014 function calling itself</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">factorial</span>(n):\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> n <= <span class=\"y\">1</span>: <span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"y\">1</span>   <span class=\"c\"># base case \u2014 ALWAYS required</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> n * factorial(n - <span class=\"y\">1</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># recursive case</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 5. DATA STRUCTURES \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-ds\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Data Structures</h2>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 160\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">Choosing the right data structure</text>\n      <g text-anchor=\"middle\">\n        <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"125\" height=\"105\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">list</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">ordered, mutable</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">duplicates OK</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(1) append</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(n) search</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">default sequence</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"160\" y=\"38\" width=\"125\" height=\"105\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#F4EFFE\" stroke=\"#D9C8FA\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">tuple</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">ordered, immutable</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">hashable (dict key)</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">faster than list</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">less memory</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">fixed data / coords</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"300\" y=\"38\" width=\"125\" height=\"105\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">set</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">unordered, mutable</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">no duplicates</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(1) lookup</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(1) add/remove</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#0E9384\">dedup + membership</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"440\" y=\"38\" width=\"240\" height=\"105\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#FEF5E7\" stroke=\"#F4D49A\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#C2710C\">dict</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">key\u2192value, ordered (3.7+)</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(1) get/set/delete</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">keys must be hashable</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">no duplicate keys</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#C2710C\">configs, caching, JSON</text>\n      </g>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <h3>Lists</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Creation and basic operations</span>\nlst = [<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">4</span>, <span class=\"y\">5</span>]\nlst.append(<span class=\"y\">6</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># [1,2,3,4,5,6]</span>\nlst.insert(<span class=\"y\">0</span>, <span class=\"y\">0</span>)       <span class=\"c\"># [0,1,2,3,4,5,6]</span>\nlst.pop()              <span class=\"c\"># removes + returns last: 6</span>\nlst.pop(<span class=\"y\">0</span>)             <span class=\"c\"># removes + returns index 0: 0</span>\nlst.remove(<span class=\"y\">3</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># removes first occurrence of value 3</span>\nlst.sort()             <span class=\"c\"># in-place sort</span>\nsorted(lst)            <span class=\"c\"># returns new sorted list</span>\nlst.reverse()          <span class=\"c\"># in-place reverse</span>\nlen(lst)               <span class=\"c\"># length</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Slicing \u2014 [start:stop:step]  (stop is exclusive)</span>\nlst = [<span class=\"y\">0</span>,<span class=\"y\">1</span>,<span class=\"y\">2</span>,<span class=\"y\">3</span>,<span class=\"y\">4</span>,<span class=\"y\">5</span>]\nlst[<span class=\"y\">1</span>:<span class=\"y\">4</span>]       <span class=\"c\"># [1, 2, 3]</span>\nlst[:<span class=\"y\">3</span>]        <span class=\"c\"># [0, 1, 2]</span>\nlst[<span class=\"y\">3</span>:]        <span class=\"c\"># [3, 4, 5]</span>\nlst[::-<span class=\"y\">1</span>]      <span class=\"c\"># [5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0]  \u2014 reverse</span>\nlst[::2]       <span class=\"c\"># [0, 2, 4]            \u2014 every other</span>\nlst[-<span class=\"y\">2</span>:]       <span class=\"c\"># [4, 5]               \u2014 last 2</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># List comprehensions \u2014 the Pythonic way</span>\nsquares   = [x**<span class=\"y\">2</span> <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">10</span>)]\nevens     = [x <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">20</span>) <span class=\"k\">if</span> x % <span class=\"y\">2</span> == <span class=\"y\">0</span>]\nmatrix    = [[i*j <span class=\"k\">for</span> j <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">3</span>)] <span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">3</span>)]  <span class=\"c\"># nested</span>\nflattened = [x <span class=\"k\">for</span> row <span class=\"k\">in</span> matrix <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> row]           <span class=\"c\"># flatten</span></div>\n\n  <h3>Dictionaries</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Creation and operations</span>\nd = {<span class=\"g\">\"name\"</span>: <span class=\"g\">\"Aman\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"age\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">30</span>}\nd[<span class=\"g\">\"city\"</span>] = <span class=\"g\">\"Noida\"</span>         <span class=\"c\"># add/update</span>\nd.get(<span class=\"g\">\"salary\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">0</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># safe get with default \u2014 no KeyError</span>\nd.pop(<span class=\"g\">\"age\"</span>)               <span class=\"c\"># remove and return value</span>\nd.keys()                   <span class=\"c\"># dict_keys view</span>\nd.values()                 <span class=\"c\"># dict_values view</span>\nd.items()                  <span class=\"c\"># dict_items view \u2014 (key, value) pairs</span>\nd.update({<span class=\"g\">\"x\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"y\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">2</span>}) <span class=\"c\"># merge another dict in</span>\n{**d, <span class=\"g\">\"z\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">3</span>}              <span class=\"c\"># merge with spread (creates new dict)</span>\nd | {<span class=\"g\">\"z\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">3</span>}               <span class=\"c\"># merge operator (Python 3.9+)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Dict comprehension</span>\nsquares = {x: x**<span class=\"y\">2</span> <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">5</span>)}\nfiltered = {k: v <span class=\"k\">for</span> k, v <span class=\"k\">in</span> d.items() <span class=\"k\">if</span> v > <span class=\"y\">10</span>}\n\n<span class=\"c\"># defaultdict \u2014 never KeyError on missing keys</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> collections <span class=\"k\">import</span> defaultdict\ndd = defaultdict(list)\ndd[<span class=\"g\">\"tags\"</span>].append(<span class=\"g\">\"python\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># auto-creates empty list if key missing</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Counter \u2014 count occurrences</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> collections <span class=\"k\">import</span> Counter\nc = Counter([<span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"b\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"c\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>])\nc.most_common(<span class=\"y\">2</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [(\"a\", 3), (\"b\", 1)]</span></div>\n\n  <h3>Sets</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\">a = {<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">4</span>}\nb = {<span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">4</span>, <span class=\"y\">5</span>, <span class=\"y\">6</span>}\na | b       <span class=\"c\"># {1,2,3,4,5,6}  union</span>\na &amp; b       <span class=\"c\"># {3, 4}          intersection</span>\na - b       <span class=\"c\"># {1, 2}          difference</span>\na ^ b       <span class=\"c\"># {1,2,5,6}       symmetric difference (in one but not both)</span>\na.issubset(b)    <span class=\"c\"># is every element of a in b?</span>\na.issuperset(b)  <span class=\"c\"># is every element of b in a?</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Deduplication pattern</span>\nunique = list(set([<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>]))  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [1, 2, 3] (order not guaranteed)</span></div>\n\n  <h3>Strings</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Strings are immutable sequences of characters</span>\ns = <span class=\"g\">\"Hello, World!\"</span>\ns.upper()          <span class=\"c\"># \"HELLO, WORLD!\"</span>\ns.lower()          <span class=\"c\"># \"hello, world!\"</span>\ns.strip()          <span class=\"c\"># remove leading/trailing whitespace</span>\ns.split(<span class=\"g\">\",\"</span>)       <span class=\"c\"># [\"Hello\", \" World!\"]</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\",\"</span>.join([<span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>,<span class=\"g\">\"b\"</span>]) <span class=\"c\"># \"a,b\"</span>\ns.replace(<span class=\"g\">\"l\"</span>,<span class=\"g\">\"L\"</span>) <span class=\"c\"># \"HeLLo, WorLd!\"</span>\ns.startswith(<span class=\"g\">\"He\"</span>) <span class=\"c\"># True</span>\ns.find(<span class=\"g\">\"World\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># 7 (index) or -1 if not found</span>\ns[<span class=\"y\">7</span>:<span class=\"y\">12</span>]            <span class=\"c\"># \"World\" \u2014 slicing works on strings too</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># String formatting</span>\nname, score = <span class=\"g\">\"Aman\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">95.5</span>\nf<span class=\"g\">\"{name} scored {score:.1f}%\"</span>           <span class=\"c\"># f-string (fastest, most readable)</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\"{} scored {:.1f}%\"</span>.format(name, score) <span class=\"c\"># .format()</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\"%s scored %.1f%%\"</span> % (name, score)      <span class=\"c\"># % formatting (old style)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Regex</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> re\npattern = re.compile(<span class=\"g\">r\"\\d+\"</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># compile for reuse</span>\nre.findall(<span class=\"g\">r\"\\d+\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"abc123def456\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [\"123\", \"456\"]</span>\nre.sub(<span class=\"g\">r\"\\s+\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\" \"</span>, text)            <span class=\"c\"># replace multiple spaces with one</span>\nre.match(<span class=\"g\">r\"^\\d{4}\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"2024-01-01\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># match at start</span>\nre.search(<span class=\"g\">r\"\\d{4}\"</span>, text)            <span class=\"c\"># match anywhere</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 6. EXCEPTIONS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-exceptions\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Exception Handling</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why this matters in ML systems</span>\n    <p>Production ML pipelines fail constantly \u2014 network timeouts, corrupt data, API rate limits, out-of-memory errors. Unhandled exceptions crash your entire pipeline at 2 AM. Good exception handling means the system logs the error, handles it gracefully, and keeps running.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Basic try/except/else/finally</span>\n<span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n    result = <span class=\"y\">10</span> / x          <span class=\"c\"># might raise ZeroDivisionError</span>\n    data = json.loads(s)      <span class=\"c\"># might raise JSONDecodeError</span>\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> ZeroDivisionError:\n    print(<span class=\"g\">\"division by zero\"</span>)\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> (ValueError, TypeError) <span class=\"k\">as</span> e:\n    print(f<span class=\"g\">\"value/type error: {e}\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># multiple exceptions</span>\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> Exception <span class=\"k\">as</span> e:\n    print(f<span class=\"g\">\"unexpected: {e}\"</span>)         <span class=\"c\"># catch-all (use sparingly)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">else</span>:\n    print(<span class=\"g\">\"no exception occurred\"</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># runs ONLY if no exception</span>\n<span class=\"k\">finally</span>:\n    cleanup()                          <span class=\"c\"># ALWAYS runs (even if exception)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Raising exceptions</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">divide</span>(a, b):\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> b == <span class=\"y\">0</span>:\n        <span class=\"k\">raise</span> ValueError(<span class=\"g\">\"b cannot be zero\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> a / b\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Re-raising \u2014 preserve original traceback</span>\n<span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n    risky()\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> SomeError <span class=\"k\">as</span> e:\n    log(e)\n    <span class=\"k\">raise</span>   <span class=\"c\"># re-raise the same exception</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Custom exception classes</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">DataValidationError</span>(ValueError):\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Raised when input data fails validation.\"\"\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, field: str, message: str):\n        self.field = field\n        super().__init__(f<span class=\"g\">\"Field '{field}': {message}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"k\">raise</span> DataValidationError(<span class=\"g\">\"age\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"must be positive\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Exception hierarchy (most specific first in except blocks)</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># BaseException</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#   \u2514\u2500\u2500 Exception</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#         \u251c\u2500\u2500 ValueError, TypeError, KeyError, IndexError</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#         \u251c\u2500\u2500 OSError \u2192 FileNotFoundError, PermissionError</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#         \u2514\u2500\u2500 RuntimeError, StopIteration, ...</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Logging exceptions (production pattern)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> logging\nlogging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO)\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n<span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n    process()\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> Exception:\n    logger.exception(<span class=\"g\">\"Processing failed\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># logs full traceback automatically</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 7. FILE HANDLING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-files\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>File Handling</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Text files</span>\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"data.txt\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"r\"</span>, encoding=<span class=\"g\">\"utf-8\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    content = f.read()           <span class=\"c\"># whole file as string</span>\n    lines = f.readlines()        <span class=\"c\"># list of lines</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> line <span class=\"k\">in</span> f:              <span class=\"c\"># line-by-line (memory efficient)</span>\n        process(line.strip())\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"output.txt\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"w\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:   <span class=\"c\"># \"w\"=write, \"a\"=append</span>\n    f.write(<span class=\"g\">\"hello\\n\"</span>)\n    f.writelines([<span class=\"g\">\"line1\\n\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"line2\\n\"</span>])\n\n<span class=\"c\"># CSV \u2014 use pandas for real work, csv module for lightweight</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> csv\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"data.csv\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    reader = csv.DictReader(f)   <span class=\"c\"># each row \u2192 dict with column names</span>\n    rows = list(reader)\n\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pandas <span class=\"k\">as</span> pd\ndf = pd.read_csv(<span class=\"g\">\"data.csv\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># the production way</span>\ndf.to_csv(<span class=\"g\">\"out.csv\"</span>, index=<span class=\"k\">False</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># JSON</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> json\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"config.json\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    config = json.load(f)        <span class=\"c\"># file \u2192 Python dict</span>\njson_str = json.dumps(config, indent=<span class=\"y\">2</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># dict \u2192 string</span>\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"out.json\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"w\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    json.dump(config, f, indent=<span class=\"y\">2</span>)       <span class=\"c\"># dict \u2192 file</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Parquet \u2014 columnar storage for large ML datasets</span>\ndf = pd.read_parquet(<span class=\"g\">\"data.parquet\"</span>)\ndf.to_parquet(<span class=\"g\">\"out.parquet\"</span>, index=<span class=\"k\">False</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Pickle \u2014 serialize any Python object</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pickle\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"model.pkl\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"wb\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:   <span class=\"c\"># \"wb\" = write binary</span>\n    pickle.dump(model, f)\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"model.pkl\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"rb\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    model = pickle.load(f)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># YAML \u2014 config files (requires PyYAML)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> yaml\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"config.yaml\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    config = yaml.safe_load(f)   <span class=\"c\"># always use safe_load, not load</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># pathlib \u2014 modern path handling (preferred over os.path)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> pathlib <span class=\"k\">import</span> Path\np = Path(<span class=\"g\">\"data\"</span>) / <span class=\"g\">\"raw\"</span> / <span class=\"g\">\"file.csv\"</span>\np.exists()            <span class=\"c\"># True/False</span>\np.mkdir(parents=<span class=\"k\">True</span>, exist_ok=<span class=\"k\">True</span>)\nlist(p.parent.glob(<span class=\"g\">\"*.csv\"</span>))   <span class=\"c\"># all CSV files</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 8. MODULES \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-modules\"><span class=\"num\">08</span>Modules & Packages</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Import styles</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> math                      <span class=\"c\"># import module</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> math <span class=\"k\">import</span> sqrt, pi        <span class=\"c\"># import specific names</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> math <span class=\"k\">import</span> *               <span class=\"c\"># import all (avoid \u2014 pollutes namespace)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np               <span class=\"c\"># alias</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> . <span class=\"k\">import</span> utils              <span class=\"c\"># relative import (inside a package)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># __name__ \u2014 module's name when imported vs run directly</span>\n<span class=\"k\">if</span> __name__ == <span class=\"g\">\"__main__\"</span>:\n    main()   <span class=\"c\"># only runs when file is executed directly, not when imported</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Package structure</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># myproject/</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#   __init__.py     \u2190 makes it a package, can define public API</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#   models/</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#     __init__.py</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#     transformer.py</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#   utils/</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#     __init__.py</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#     preprocessing.py</span></div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Virtual environments \u2014 isolate project dependencies</span>\npython -m venv .venv           <span class=\"c\"># create</span>\nsource .venv/bin/activate      <span class=\"c\"># activate (Linux/Mac)</span>\n.venv\\Scripts\\activate         <span class=\"c\"># activate (Windows)</span>\npip install -r requirements.txt\n\n<span class=\"c\"># requirements.txt</span>\nnumpy==1.26.0\npandas>=2.0.0\ntorch>=2.1.0\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Poetry \u2014 modern dependency management</span>\npoetry new myproject           <span class=\"c\"># create project</span>\npoetry add numpy pandas        <span class=\"c\"># add dependencies</span>\npoetry add --group dev pytest  <span class=\"c\"># dev-only dependency</span>\npoetry install                 <span class=\"c\"># install all</span>\npoetry run python main.py      <span class=\"c\"># run in poetry env</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 9. OOP \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-oop\"><span class=\"num\">09</span>Object-Oriented Programming</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why OOP matters for ML</span>\n    <p>Every ML framework you use is OOP: PyTorch's <code>nn.Module</code>, sklearn's estimators, LangChain's Runnables. Understanding OOP means you can extend frameworks, debug inheritance issues, and write clean ML pipelines instead of spaghetti scripts.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <h3>Classes and Objects</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">MLModel</span>:\n    <span class=\"c\"># Class attribute \u2014 shared across ALL instances</span>\n    model_type = <span class=\"g\">\"base\"</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, name: str, lr: float = <span class=\"y\">0.001</span>):\n        <span class=\"c\"># Instance attributes \u2014 unique to each instance</span>\n        self.name = name\n        self.lr = lr\n        self._weights = []          <span class=\"c\"># convention: _ = \"private\" (not enforced)</span>\n        self.__secret = <span class=\"g\">\"hidden\"</span>   <span class=\"c\"># name-mangled: _MLModel__secret</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">train</span>(self, data):\n        <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Instance method \u2014 receives self\"\"\"</span>\n        self._weights = self._fit(data)\n\n    <span class=\"o\">@classmethod</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">from_config</span>(cls, config: dict) -> <span class=\"g\">\"MLModel\"</span>:\n        <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Class method \u2014 receives cls, used as alternative constructor\"\"\"</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> cls(config[<span class=\"g\">\"name\"</span>], config.get(<span class=\"g\">\"lr\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">0.001</span>))\n\n    <span class=\"o\">@staticmethod</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">normalize</span>(x):\n        <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Static method \u2014 no self/cls, utility function\"\"\"</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> (x - x.mean()) / x.std()\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__repr__</span>(self) -> str:\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> f<span class=\"g\">\"MLModel(name={self.name!r}, lr={self.lr})\"</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__str__</span>(self) -> str:\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> f<span class=\"g\">\"Model: {self.name}\"</span>\n\nmodel = MLModel(<span class=\"g\">\"bert\"</span>, lr=<span class=\"y\">2e-5</span>)\nmodel2 = MLModel.from_config({<span class=\"g\">\"name\"</span>: <span class=\"g\">\"gpt\"</span>})</div>\n\n  <h3>The Four Pillars</h3>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 160\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">Four pillars of OOP \u2014 what each one actually does</text>\n      <g text-anchor=\"middle\">\n        <rect x=\"15\" y=\"38\" width=\"155\" height=\"110\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">Encapsulation</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Hide internal data.</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Expose only what's needed</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">via methods.</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"128\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">_private, __mangled</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">@property getters/setters</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"185\" y=\"38\" width=\"155\" height=\"110\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Abstraction</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Hide HOW something</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">works. Show only WHAT</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">it does.</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"128\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Abstract base classes</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Interfaces (ABC)</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"355\" y=\"38\" width=\"155\" height=\"110\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#F4EFFE\" stroke=\"#D9C8FA\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">Inheritance</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Child class reuses</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">parent behaviour.</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Extend without rewrite.</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"128\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">class Child(Parent):</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">super().__init__()</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"525\" y=\"38\" width=\"160\" height=\"110\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#FEF5E7\" stroke=\"#F4D49A\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#C2710C\">Polymorphism</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Same interface,</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">different behaviour.</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Method overriding.</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"128\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#C2710C\">model.predict(data)</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#C2710C\">works for any model</text>\n      </g>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># INHERITANCE</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">BaseModel</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, name):\n        self.name = name\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">predict</span>(self, x):\n        <span class=\"k\">raise</span> NotImplementedError\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">LinearModel</span>(BaseModel):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, name, lr=<span class=\"y\">0.01</span>):\n        super().__init__(name)    <span class=\"c\"># call parent __init__</span>\n        self.lr = lr\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">predict</span>(self, x):        <span class=\"c\"># override parent method</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self.weights @ x\n\n<span class=\"c\"># ABSTRACTION with ABC</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> abc <span class=\"k\">import</span> ABC, abstractmethod\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Encoder</span>(ABC):\n    <span class=\"o\">@abstractmethod</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">encode</span>(self, text: str) -> list[float]:\n        <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Must be implemented by subclass.\"\"\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">BERTEncoder</span>(Encoder):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">encode</span>(self, text):\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> bert_model(text)   <span class=\"c\"># concrete implementation</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># POLYMORPHISM \u2014 same code works for any encoder</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">embed_documents</span>(docs: list, encoder: Encoder) -> list:\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> [encoder.encode(d) <span class=\"k\">for</span> d <span class=\"k\">in</span> docs]  <span class=\"c\"># works for ANY encoder subclass</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># ENCAPSULATION with property</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Temperature</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, celsius):\n        self._celsius = celsius\n\n    <span class=\"o\">@property</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">celsius</span>(self):           <span class=\"c\"># getter</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self._celsius\n\n    <span class=\"o\">@celsius.setter</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">celsius</span>(self, value):    <span class=\"c\"># setter with validation</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">if</span> value < -<span class=\"y\">273.15</span>:\n            <span class=\"k\">raise</span> ValueError(<span class=\"g\">\"Below absolute zero!\"</span>)\n        self._celsius = value</div>\n\n  <h3>Magic (Dunder) Methods</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Vector</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, x, y):  self.x, self.y = x, y\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__repr__</span>(self):        <span class=\"k\">return</span> f<span class=\"g\">\"Vector({self.x}, {self.y})\"</span>   <span class=\"c\"># repr()</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__str__</span>(self):         <span class=\"k\">return</span> f<span class=\"g\">\"({self.x}, {self.y})\"</span>         <span class=\"c\"># str()</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__len__</span>(self):         <span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"y\">2</span>                               <span class=\"c\"># len()</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__add__</span>(self, other):  <span class=\"k\">return</span> Vector(self.x+other.x, self.y+other.y) <span class=\"c\"># v1 + v2</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__mul__</span>(self, scalar): <span class=\"k\">return</span> Vector(self.x*scalar, self.y*scalar)  <span class=\"c\"># v * 3</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__eq__</span>(self, other):   <span class=\"k\">return</span> self.x==other.x <span class=\"k\">and</span> self.y==other.y <span class=\"c\"># v1 == v2</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__hash__</span>(self):        <span class=\"k\">return</span> hash((self.x, self.y))           <span class=\"c\"># use in dict/set</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__contains__</span>(self, v): <span class=\"k\">return</span> v <span class=\"k\">in</span> [self.x, self.y]           <span class=\"c\"># x in v</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__getitem__</span>(self, i):  <span class=\"k\">return</span> [self.x, self.y][i]             <span class=\"c\"># v[0]</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__iter__</span>(self):        <span class=\"k\">return</span> iter([self.x, self.y])          <span class=\"c\"># for x in v</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__bool__</span>(self):        <span class=\"k\">return</span> bool(self.x <span class=\"k\">or</span> self.y)         <span class=\"c\"># if v:</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__call__</span>(self, scale): <span class=\"k\">return</span> self * scale                    <span class=\"c\"># v(2)</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 10. ITERATORS / GENERATORS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-iterators\"><span class=\"num\">10</span>Iterators & Generators</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why generators matter for ML</span>\n    <p>Loading a 100GB dataset into a list would crash your machine. A generator loads and processes one batch at a time, keeping only one batch in memory at any moment. PyTorch's DataLoader uses this pattern. Understanding generators = understanding how large-scale training actually works.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 140\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">List vs Generator \u2014 memory usage comparison</text>\n      <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"290\" height=\"90\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#FDEAEF\" stroke=\"#F6C0CF\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">List \u2014 all values in memory</text>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">[x**2 for x in range(1_000_000)]</text>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">~8 MB RAM immediately</text>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"115\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">All computed upfront</text>\n      <rect x=\"390\" y=\"38\" width=\"290\" height=\"90\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Generator \u2014 one value at a time</text>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">(x**2 for x in range(1_000_000))</text>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">~120 bytes RAM</text>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"115\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Computed lazily on next()</text>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Iterator protocol \u2014 __iter__ and __next__</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">CountUp</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, limit): self.limit, self.current = limit, <span class=\"y\">0</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__iter__</span>(self): <span class=\"k\">return</span> self            <span class=\"c\"># returns itself</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__next__</span>(self):\n        <span class=\"k\">if</span> self.current >= self.limit:\n            <span class=\"k\">raise</span> StopIteration               <span class=\"c\"># signals end of iteration</span>\n        self.current += <span class=\"y\">1</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self.current\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> n <span class=\"k\">in</span> CountUp(<span class=\"y\">3</span>): print(n)  <span class=\"c\"># 1, 2, 3</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Generator function \u2014 simpler way using yield</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">count_up</span>(limit):\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">1</span>, limit + <span class=\"y\">1</span>):\n        <span class=\"k\">yield</span> i   <span class=\"c\"># pauses here, returns value, resumes on next()</span>\n\ngen = count_up(<span class=\"y\">3</span>)\nnext(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># 1</span>\nnext(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># 2</span>\nnext(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># 3</span>\nnext(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># StopIteration</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Real ML use case \u2014 batch generator</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">batch_generator</span>(data, batch_size=<span class=\"y\">32</span>):\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Yields one batch at a time \u2014 never loads full dataset into memory.\"\"\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">0</span>, len(data), batch_size):\n        <span class=\"k\">yield</span> data[i:i + batch_size]\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> batch <span class=\"k\">in</span> batch_generator(huge_dataset):\n    model.train(batch)   <span class=\"c\"># only one batch in memory at a time</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Generator expression (lazy list comprehension)</span>\ngen = (x**<span class=\"y\">2</span> <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">1_000_000</span>))   <span class=\"c\"># () not []</span>\ntotal = sum(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># computed lazily, never all in memory\n\n# yield from \u2014 delegate to another generator</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">chain</span>(*iterables):\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> it <span class=\"k\">in</span> iterables:\n        <span class=\"k\">yield from</span> it   <span class=\"c\"># same as: for x in it: yield x</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 11. DECORATORS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-decorators\"><span class=\"num\">11</span>Decorators</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">What a decorator is \u2014 before any code</span>\n    <p>A decorator is a function that takes another function as input and returns a modified version of it. <code>@timer</code> above a function definition is just shorthand for <code>my_function = timer(my_function)</code>. That's it. The @ syntax is pure syntactic sugar.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Step 1: understand closures first</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">multiplier</span>(factor):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">multiply</span>(x):\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> x * factor    <span class=\"c\"># inner function \"captures\" outer variable</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> multiply\n\ndouble = multiplier(<span class=\"y\">2</span>)\ndouble(<span class=\"y\">5</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 10   (factor=2 is remembered)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Step 2: basic decorator</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> time\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> functools <span class=\"k\">import</span> wraps\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">timer</span>(func):\n    <span class=\"o\">@wraps</span>(func)   <span class=\"c\"># preserves func's __name__, __doc__ etc.</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">wrapper</span>(*args, **kwargs):\n        start = time.time()\n        result = func(*args, **kwargs)     <span class=\"c\"># call original function</span>\n        end = time.time()\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"{func.__name__} took {end-start:.4f}s\"</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> result\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> wrapper\n\n<span class=\"o\">@timer</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">train_model</span>(data):      <span class=\"c\"># same as: train_model = timer(train_model)</span>\n    time.sleep(<span class=\"y\">1</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"g\">\"done\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Step 3: parameterized decorator (decorator factory)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">retry</span>(max_attempts=<span class=\"y\">3</span>, exceptions=(Exception,)):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">decorator</span>(func):\n        <span class=\"o\">@wraps</span>(func)\n        <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">wrapper</span>(*args, **kwargs):\n            <span class=\"k\">for</span> attempt <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(max_attempts):\n                <span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n                    <span class=\"k\">return</span> func(*args, **kwargs)\n                <span class=\"k\">except</span> exceptions <span class=\"k\">as</span> e:\n                    <span class=\"k\">if</span> attempt == max_attempts - <span class=\"y\">1</span>: <span class=\"k\">raise</span>\n                    print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Retry {attempt+1}/{max_attempts}: {e}\"</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> wrapper\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> decorator\n\n<span class=\"o\">@retry</span>(max_attempts=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, exceptions=(ConnectionError,))\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">call_api</span>(url):\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> requests.get(url)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Multiple decorators \u2014 applied bottom to top</span>\n<span class=\"o\">@timer</span>\n<span class=\"o\">@retry</span>(max_attempts=<span class=\"y\">3</span>)\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">fetch_data</span>(url): ...\n<span class=\"c\"># equivalent to: fetch_data = timer(retry(max_attempts=3)(fetch_data))</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 12. CONTEXT MANAGERS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-context\"><span class=\"num\">12</span>Context Managers</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The problem they solve</span>\n    <p><code>with open(\"file.txt\") as f:</code> \u2014 you've used this countless times. But why? Because even if an exception occurs inside the <code>with</code> block, the file is guaranteed to close. Without context managers, a crash mid-read would leave the file handle open \u2014 a resource leak. Context managers guarantee cleanup regardless of how the block exits.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># How context managers work internally</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Timer</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__enter__</span>(self):\n        self.start = time.time()\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self          <span class=\"c\"># value assigned to \"as\" variable</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__exit__</span>(self, exc_type, exc_val, exc_tb):\n        <span class=\"c\"># exc_type/val/tb are None if no exception occurred</span>\n        elapsed = time.time() - self.start\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Elapsed: {elapsed:.3f}s\"</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"k\">False</span>  <span class=\"c\"># False = don't suppress exceptions</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> Timer() <span class=\"k\">as</span> t:\n    time.sleep(<span class=\"y\">0.5</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># always prints elapsed, even if exception</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># contextlib \u2014 simpler way with generators</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> contextlib <span class=\"k\">import</span> contextmanager\n\n<span class=\"o\">@contextmanager</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">managed_db_connection</span>(url):\n    conn = connect(url)\n    <span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n        <span class=\"k\">yield</span> conn           <span class=\"c\"># everything before yield = __enter__</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">finally</span>:\n        conn.close()         <span class=\"c\"># everything in finally = __exit__</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> managed_db_connection(<span class=\"g\">\"postgres://...\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> conn:\n    conn.execute(<span class=\"g\">\"SELECT 1\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># conn.close() always called after</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Multiple context managers in one line</span>\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"in.txt\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> infile, open(<span class=\"g\">\"out.txt\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"w\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> outfile:\n    outfile.write(infile.read())</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 13. THREADING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-threads\"><span class=\"num\">13</span>Multithreading</h2>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 150\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">GIL: why threads don't speed up CPU work in Python</text>\n      <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"100\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#FDEAEF\" stroke=\"#F6C0CF\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">CPU-bound (threads DON'T help)</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">GIL: only 1 thread runs Python</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">bytecode at a time</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"118\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">Use multiprocessing instead</text>\n      <rect x=\"380\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"100\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">I/O-bound (threads HELP)</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">GIL released while waiting</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">for network/disk/sleep</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"118\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">API calls, file reads: great!</text>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> threading\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> concurrent.futures <span class=\"k\">import</span> ThreadPoolExecutor\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Basic thread</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">fetch_url</span>(url):\n    response = requests.get(url)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> response.json()\n\nthread = threading.Thread(target=fetch_url, args=(<span class=\"g\">\"http://api.example.com\"</span>,))\nthread.start()\nthread.join()   <span class=\"c\"># wait for thread to finish</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># ThreadPoolExecutor \u2014 the production pattern</span>\nurls = [<span class=\"g\">\"http://api1.com\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"http://api2.com\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"http://api3.com\"</span>]\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=<span class=\"y\">10</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> executor:\n    results = list(executor.map(fetch_url, urls))   <span class=\"c\"># parallel API calls</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Thread safety \u2014 Lock prevents race conditions</span>\nlock = threading.Lock()\ncounter = <span class=\"y\">0</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">increment</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">global</span> counter\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> lock:                 <span class=\"c\"># only one thread at a time</span>\n        counter += <span class=\"y\">1</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Race condition example (WITHOUT lock)</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Thread 1: reads counter=5</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Thread 2: reads counter=5</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Thread 1: writes counter=6</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Thread 2: writes counter=6  \u2190 WRONG \u2014 should be 7</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 14. MULTIPROCESSING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-multiproc\"><span class=\"num\">14</span>Multiprocessing</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> concurrent.futures <span class=\"k\">import</span> ProcessPoolExecutor\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> multiprocessing <span class=\"k\">as</span> mp\n\n<span class=\"c\"># ProcessPoolExecutor \u2014 the clean API (use this first)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">process_chunk</span>(chunk):\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"CPU-intensive work \u2014 runs in a separate process\"\"\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> [compute(x) <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> chunk]\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> ProcessPoolExecutor(max_workers=mp.cpu_count()) <span class=\"k\">as</span> executor:\n    results = list(executor.map(process_chunk, data_chunks))\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Lower-level multiprocessing for shared state</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">worker</span>(queue, result_queue):\n    <span class=\"k\">while True</span>:\n        item = queue.get()\n        <span class=\"k\">if</span> item <span class=\"k\">is None</span>: <span class=\"k\">break</span>   <span class=\"c\"># poison pill \u2014 signal to stop</span>\n        result_queue.put(process(item))\n\ntask_queue = mp.Queue()\nresult_queue = mp.Queue()\nworkers = [mp.Process(target=worker, args=(task_queue, result_queue))\n           <span class=\"k\">for</span> _ <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">4</span>)]\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> w <span class=\"k\">in</span> workers: w.start()\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> item <span class=\"k\">in</span> data: task_queue.put(item)\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> _ <span class=\"k\">in</span> workers: task_queue.put(<span class=\"k\">None</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># send poison pills</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> w <span class=\"k\">in</span> workers: w.join()\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Shared memory (Python 3.8+) \u2014 for large arrays</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> multiprocessing <span class=\"k\">import</span> shared_memory\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\nshm = shared_memory.SharedMemory(create=<span class=\"k\">True</span>, size=<span class=\"y\">1000</span>*<span class=\"y\">8</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># 1000 float64s</span>\narr = np.ndarray((<span class=\"y\">1000</span>,), dtype=np.float64, buffer=shm.buf)  <span class=\"c\"># no copying!</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 15. ASYNCIO \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-async\"><span class=\"num\">15</span>Asyncio \u2014 Asynchronous Programming</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The key mental model</span>\n    <p>Async is NOT parallel. It's single-threaded. The trick: when one task is waiting (for a network response, file read, DB query), instead of blocking, Python switches to another task and makes progress there. When the wait is done, it switches back. All tasks share one thread \u2014 but no time is wasted waiting.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 140\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">Async: switching tasks while waiting (single thread)</text>\n      <!-- Sync -->\n      <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"290\" height=\"90\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#FDEAEF\" stroke=\"#F6C0CF\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"58\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">Synchronous \u2014 blocking</text>\n      <rect x=\"35\" y=\"68\" width=\"60\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#D92D5C\"/>\n      <text x=\"65\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">API call</text>\n      <rect x=\"95\" y=\"68\" width=\"80\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#E7E8F0\"/>\n      <text x=\"135\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#999\">waiting...</text>\n      <rect x=\"175\" y=\"68\" width=\"50\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#D92D5C\"/>\n      <text x=\"200\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">result</text>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"115\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">Thread blocked for entire wait</text>\n      <!-- Async -->\n      <rect x=\"390\" y=\"38\" width=\"290\" height=\"90\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"58\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Async \u2014 non-blocking</text>\n      <rect x=\"405\" y=\"68\" width=\"60\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#0E9384\"/>\n      <text x=\"435\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">API call</text>\n      <rect x=\"465\" y=\"68\" width=\"80\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#4F46E5\"/>\n      <text x=\"505\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">other work!</text>\n      <rect x=\"545\" y=\"68\" width=\"60\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#0E9384\"/>\n      <text x=\"575\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">result</text>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"115\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Switch to other tasks while waiting</text>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> asyncio\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> aiohttp\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Basic coroutine \u2014 defined with async def</span>\n<span class=\"k\">async def</span> <span class=\"o\">fetch_data</span>(url: str) -> dict:\n    <span class=\"k\">async with</span> aiohttp.ClientSession() <span class=\"k\">as</span> session:\n        <span class=\"k\">async with</span> session.get(url) <span class=\"k\">as</span> response:\n            <span class=\"k\">return await</span> response.json()   <span class=\"c\"># await = \"pause here, let others run\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Run a single coroutine</span>\nresult = asyncio.run(fetch_data(<span class=\"g\">\"http://api.example.com\"</span>))\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Run multiple coroutines concurrently</span>\n<span class=\"k\">async def</span> <span class=\"o\">main</span>():\n    urls = [<span class=\"g\">\"http://api1.com\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"http://api2.com\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"http://api3.com\"</span>]\n    tasks = [fetch_data(url) <span class=\"k\">for</span> url <span class=\"k\">in</span> urls]\n    results = <span class=\"k\">await</span> asyncio.gather(*tasks)   <span class=\"c\"># runs all 3 concurrently!</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> results\n\n<span class=\"c\"># asyncio.gather vs asyncio.wait</span>\nresults = <span class=\"k\">await</span> asyncio.gather(*tasks)           <span class=\"c\"># all or nothing</span>\ndone, pending = <span class=\"k\">await</span> asyncio.wait(tasks,          <span class=\"c\"># fine-grained control</span>\n                                    timeout=<span class=\"y\">5.0</span>,\n                                    return_when=asyncio.FIRST_COMPLETED)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Async generator \u2014 streaming large datasets</span>\n<span class=\"k\">async def</span> <span class=\"o\">stream_records</span>(db):\n    <span class=\"k\">async for</span> row <span class=\"k\">in</span> db.execute(<span class=\"g\">\"SELECT * FROM huge_table\"</span>):\n        <span class=\"k\">yield</span> row    <span class=\"c\"># processes one row at a time without loading all</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Semaphore \u2014 limit concurrent requests (avoid rate limiting)</span>\nsem = asyncio.Semaphore(<span class=\"y\">10</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># max 10 concurrent requests</span>\n<span class=\"k\">async def</span> <span class=\"o\">rate_limited_fetch</span>(url):\n    <span class=\"k\">async with</span> sem:\n        <span class=\"k\">return await</span> fetch_data(url)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 16. TESTING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-testing\"><span class=\"num\">16</span>Testing & Debugging</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># pytest \u2014 the standard Python testing framework</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># File: test_model.py (pytest finds files starting with test_)</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pytest\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> myproject.model <span class=\"k\">import</span> LinearModel\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Basic test \u2014 function starting with test_</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_predict_shape</span>():\n    model = LinearModel(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">10</span>, output_dim=<span class=\"y\">3</span>)\n    output = model.predict([[<span class=\"y\">1</span>]*<span class=\"y\">10</span>])\n    assert output.shape == (<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># pytest shows diff on failure</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># pytest.raises \u2014 test exceptions</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_invalid_input</span>():\n    model = LinearModel(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> pytest.raises(ValueError, match=<span class=\"g\">\"expected 10 features\"</span>):\n        model.predict([[<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>]])   <span class=\"c\"># wrong shape \u2014 should raise ValueError</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Parameterized tests \u2014 run same test with multiple inputs</span>\n<span class=\"o\">@pytest.mark.parametrize</span>(<span class=\"g\">\"input,expected\"</span>, [\n    ([<span class=\"y\">0</span>]*<span class=\"y\">10</span>, [<span class=\"y\">0</span>]*<span class=\"y\">3</span>),\n    ([<span class=\"y\">1</span>]*<span class=\"y\">10</span>, [<span class=\"y\">1</span>]*<span class=\"y\">3</span>),\n])\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_predict_values</span>(input, expected):\n    model = LinearModel.identity(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\n    assert model.predict([input]) == [expected]\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Fixtures \u2014 reusable setup</span>\n<span class=\"o\">@pytest.fixture</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">trained_model</span>():\n    model = LinearModel(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\n    model.fit(training_data)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> model                   <span class=\"c\"># every test that needs it gets a fresh one</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_with_fixture</span>(trained_model):\n    assert trained_model.accuracy > <span class=\"y\">0.8</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Mocking \u2014 replace external dependencies</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> unittest.mock <span class=\"k\">import</span> patch, MagicMock\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_api_call</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> patch(<span class=\"g\">\"myproject.client.requests.get\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> mock_get:\n        mock_get.return_value.json.return_value = {<span class=\"g\">\"status\"</span>: <span class=\"g\">\"ok\"</span>}\n        result = call_api(<span class=\"g\">\"http://api.example.com\"</span>)\n        assert result == {<span class=\"g\">\"status\"</span>: <span class=\"g\">\"ok\"</span>}\n        mock_get.assert_called_once_with(<span class=\"g\">\"http://api.example.com\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Profiling \u2014 find where time is spent</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> cProfile, pstats\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> cProfile.Profile() <span class=\"k\">as</span> pr:\n    my_slow_function()\n\nstats = pstats.Stats(pr)\nstats.sort_stats(<span class=\"g\">\"cumulative\"</span>)\nstats.print_stats(<span class=\"y\">10</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># top 10 time-consuming functions\n\n# timeit \u2014 benchmark small snippets</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> timeit\ntimeit.timeit(<span class=\"g\">\"[x**2 for x in range(1000)]\"</span>, number=<span class=\"y\">1000</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># run 1000 times, return total\n\n# pdb \u2014 interactive debugger</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pdb\npdb.set_trace()    <span class=\"c\"># drops into debugger at this line</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Commands: n(ext), s(tep), c(ontinue), l(ist), p variable, q(uit)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># breakpoint() \u2014 Python 3.7+ cleaner syntax</span>\nbreakpoint()       <span class=\"c\"># same as pdb.set_trace() but respects PYTHONBREAKPOINT env var\n\n# Logging \u2014 structured observability for production</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> logging\n\nlogging.basicConfig(\n    level=logging.DEBUG,\n    format=<span class=\"g\">'%(asctime)s %(name)s %(levelname)s %(message)s'</span>,\n    handlers=[\n        logging.StreamHandler(),               <span class=\"c\"># stdout</span>\n        logging.FileHandler(<span class=\"g\">\"app.log\"</span>),       <span class=\"c\"># file</span>\n    ]\n)\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nlogger.debug(<span class=\"g\">\"debugging detail\"</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># dev only</span>\nlogger.info(<span class=\"g\">\"model loaded\"</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># normal operations</span>\nlogger.warning(<span class=\"g\">\"GPU memory low\"</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># something unexpected</span>\nlogger.error(<span class=\"g\">\"prediction failed\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># error, but continuing</span>\nlogger.critical(<span class=\"g\">\"database down\"</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># entire system affected</span>\nlogger.exception(<span class=\"g\">\"unhandled error\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># error + full traceback</span></div>\n\n  <!-- Q&A -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-qa\"><span class=\"num\">17</span>Interview Q&A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\"><h3>Answer before revealing</h3><button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button></div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the difference between is and ==?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">== checks value equality \u2014 do the two objects have the same value? is checks object identity \u2014 are the two variables pointing to the exact same object in memory (same id()). Example: a = [1,2]; b = [1,2]; a == b is True (same values) but a is b is False (different list objects). Important: always use is for None checks (a is None, not a == None) because == calls __eq__ which can be overridden.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Mutable vs immutable \u2014 give examples and explain why it matters.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Mutable: list, dict, set, bytearray \u2014 can be changed after creation. Immutable: int, float, str, tuple, frozenset \u2014 every \"change\" creates a new object. Matters because: (1) mutable objects passed to functions can be modified in place, causing unexpected side effects. (2) Only hashable (immutable) objects can be dict keys or set elements. (3) Aliasing bug: b = a creates a second reference to the same mutable object \u2014 modifying through a also changes b.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the GIL and when does it matter?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">The Global Interpreter Lock is a mutex in CPython that prevents multiple threads from executing Python bytecode simultaneously. Only one thread runs at a time. For CPU-bound tasks (computation, ML training), threads provide no speedup \u2014 use multiprocessing instead. For I/O-bound tasks (API calls, file reads, network), the GIL is released while waiting for I/O, so threads do help. Alternatively, use asyncio for I/O-bound work with a single thread.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>How does a generator save memory compared to a list?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">A list computes and stores all values upfront in memory. A generator computes values lazily \u2014 one at a time, only when next() is called. For [x**2 for x in range(1_000_000)], the list allocates ~8MB immediately. The equivalent generator (x**2 for x in range(1_000_000)) uses ~120 bytes \u2014 just enough to store the current state. Critical for ML: batch generators process large datasets without loading them entirely into memory.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is a decorator and how do you implement one?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">A decorator is a function that takes a function and returns a modified function. @timer above a function is syntactic sugar for func = timer(func). Implementation: the decorator defines an inner wrapper function that adds behaviour before/after calling the original function, then returns the wrapper. Always use @functools.wraps(func) on the wrapper to preserve the original function's __name__ and __doc__ attributes.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>When would you use multiprocessing vs threading vs asyncio?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Threading: I/O-bound tasks where you want multiple concurrent operations \u2014 API calls, file reads, DB queries. GIL is released during I/O so threads make real progress in parallel. Multiprocessing: CPU-bound tasks \u2014 data transformation, parallel ML training, heavy computation. Each process has its own Python interpreter and GIL, so true parallelism is achieved. Asyncio: I/O-bound tasks where you control all the code and want maximum efficiency with minimal overhead. Single thread, no locking needed, most efficient for high-concurrency I/O like web servers.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Explain SOLID principles briefly.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Single Responsibility: one class, one reason to change. Open/Closed: open for extension (add subclass), closed for modification (don't change existing code). Liskov Substitution: subclass can replace parent without breaking code \u2014 if Bird has fly(), and Penguin(Bird) overrides fly() to raise NotImplementedError, that violates LSP. Interface Segregation: don't force classes to implement methods they don't use \u2014 split large interfaces. Dependency Inversion: depend on abstractions (ABC/interfaces), not concrete implementations. Allows easy swapping of components.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is shallow copy vs deep copy?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Shallow copy (list.copy(), copy.copy(), list slicing): creates a new container but the elements inside are the same objects. So if the list contains mutable objects (like nested lists), those inner objects are shared. Modifying a nested list in the copy also modifies the original. Deep copy (copy.deepcopy()): recursively copies everything \u2014 new container AND new copies of all nested objects. No sharing. Use deep copy when you have nested mutable structures and need true independence between original and copy.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "py_fundamentals": "<main>\n  <h1>Python Fundamentals</h1>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pyf-vars\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Variables & Memory</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Labels, not boxes. id(), is vs ==</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pyf-types\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Data Types</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">int, float, bool, str, bytes, type conversion</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pyf-mutability\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Mutable vs Immutable</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">The most important distinction in Python</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pyf-operators\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Operators</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">All 7 types \u2014 arithmetic, bitwise, walrus</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pyf-control\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Control Flow</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">if/else, loops, break/continue, pattern matching</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"pyf-functions\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Functions</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">*args, **kwargs, scope, closures, lambda</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n    <h2>Revision</h2>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>Variables are labels, not boxes.</strong> <code>b = a</code> makes both names point at the same object. Mutating via <code>a</code> also changes what <code>b</code> sees if the object is mutable.</li>\n      <li><strong>is vs ==:</strong> <code>==</code> checks value. <code>is</code> checks identity (same object in memory). Always use <code>is None</code>, never <code>== None</code>.</li>\n      <li><strong>Mutable:</strong> list, dict, set \u2014 change in place. <strong>Immutable:</strong> int, float, str, tuple \u2014 every \"change\" creates a new object.</li>\n      <li><strong>Falsy values:</strong> <code>0</code>, <code>\"\"</code>, <code>[]</code>, <code>{}</code>, <code>None</code>, <code>False</code>. Everything else is truthy.</li>\n      <li><strong>Short-circuit:</strong> <code>and</code> stops at first False. <code>or</code> stops at first True. <code>0 or \"default\"</code> \u2192 <code>\"default\"</code>.</li>\n      <li><strong>Walrus operator :=</strong> assigns and evaluates in one expression. <code>while chunk := f.read(1024):</code></li>\n      <li><strong>for...else:</strong> the <code>else</code> block runs only if the loop completed without a <code>break</code>. Useful for search patterns.</li>\n      <li><strong>*args</strong> = variable positional args (tuple inside function). <strong>**kwargs</strong> = variable keyword args (dict inside function).</li>\n      <li><strong>LEGB scope:</strong> Local \u2192 Enclosing \u2192 Global \u2192 Built-in. <code>nonlocal</code> modifies enclosing scope. <code>global</code> modifies module scope.</li>\n      <li><strong>Mutable default argument trap:</strong> <code>def f(lst=[])</code> \u2014 the list is created once at function definition, shared across all calls. Always use <code>None</code> as default.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 1. VARIABLES & MEMORY \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"pyf-vars\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Variables & Memory \u2014 labels, not boxes</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The mental model that changes everything</span>\n    <p>In most languages, a variable <em>is</em> a box \u2014 it holds a value. In Python, a variable is a <em>label</em> (a name tag) that points to an object somewhere in memory. Multiple labels can point to the same object. When you do <code>b = a</code>, you're not copying anything \u2014 you're giving the same object a second label.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 170\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">b = a creates two labels pointing to ONE object</text>\n      <rect x=\"40\" y=\"50\" width=\"70\" height=\"32\" rx=\"7\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"75\" y=\"71\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">a</text>\n      <rect x=\"40\" y=\"100\" width=\"70\" height=\"32\" rx=\"7\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"75\" y=\"121\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">b</text>\n      <path d=\"M110 66 Q200 66 260 90\" stroke=\"#4F46E5\" stroke-width=\"2\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#pfa)\"/>\n      <path d=\"M110 116 Q200 116 260 100\" stroke=\"#4F46E5\" stroke-width=\"2\" fill=\"none\" marker-end=\"url(#pfa)\"/>\n      <rect x=\"260\" y=\"60\" width=\"160\" height=\"60\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"340\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">[1, 2, 3]</text>\n      <text x=\"340\" y=\"108\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">id: 0x7f3a4b2c (same!)</text>\n      <text x=\"490\" y=\"70\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">a.append(4)</text>\n      <text x=\"490\" y=\"88\" font-size=\"10\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">print(b) \u2192 [1,2,3,4]</text>\n      <text x=\"490\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">b also changed \u2014 same list!</text>\n      <text x=\"490\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Both labels point to one object.</text>\n      <defs><marker id=\"pfa\" markerWidth=\"7\" markerHeight=\"7\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"3\" orient=\"auto\"><path d=\"M0,0 L5,3 L0,6 Z\" fill=\"#4F46E5\"/></marker></defs>\n    </svg>\n    <figcaption>Both <code>a</code> and <code>b</code> point to the same list. Mutating through <code>a</code> also affects <code>b</code> \u2014 this surprises nearly everyone and causes real production bugs.</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Variable</span>\n    <p>A name bound to an object in Python's memory. Variables don't store values \u2014 they store <strong>references</strong> (memory addresses). The function <code>id(x)</code> returns the memory address of the object <code>x</code> points to. Two variables are the same object if and only if <code>id(a) == id(b)</code>, which is also what <code>a is b</code> checks.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Variables are labels \u2014 rebinding doesn't affect other labels</span>\na = [<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>]\nb = a             <span class=\"c\"># b now points to the SAME list as a</span>\nprint(id(a) == id(b))  <span class=\"c\"># True \u2014 same object</span>\nprint(a <span class=\"k\">is</span> b)         <span class=\"c\"># True \u2014 same identity</span>\n\nb = [<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>]       <span class=\"c\"># b NOW points to a NEW list</span>\nprint(a <span class=\"k\">is</span> b)         <span class=\"c\"># False \u2014 different objects, even though values equal</span>\nprint(a == b)          <span class=\"c\"># True  \u2014 same values</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Mutation vs rebinding \u2014 the critical distinction</span>\na = [<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>]\nb = a\na.append(<span class=\"y\">4</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># MUTATION \u2014 modifies the object both a and b point to</span>\nprint(b)         <span class=\"c\"># [1, 2, 3, 4] \u2014 b sees it too\n\n</span>a = [<span class=\"y\">99</span>]        <span class=\"c\"># REBINDING \u2014 a now points to a NEW object</span>\nprint(b)         <span class=\"c\"># [1, 2, 3, 4] \u2014 b still points to the old object</span></div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">is vs == \u2014 the classic interview trap</span>\n    <p><code>==</code> calls <code>__eq__</code> to compare <strong>values</strong>. <code>is</code> compares <strong>identity</strong> (same memory address).<br><br>\n    Python caches small integers (-5 to 256) and short strings, so <code>a = 42; b = 42; a is b</code> happens to be True \u2014 but this is an implementation detail you should never rely on.<br><br>\n    <strong>Rule:</strong> Use <code>is</code> only for <code>None</code>, <code>True</code>, <code>False</code> checks. Use <code>==</code> for value comparisons.</p>\n    <div class=\"fx\">a = <span class=\"y\">1000</span>\nb = <span class=\"y\">1000</span>\nprint(a == b)  <span class=\"c\"># True  (same value)</span>\nprint(a <span class=\"k\">is</span> b)  <span class=\"c\"># False (different objects \u2014 1000 not cached)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Always use is for None:</span>\n<span class=\"k\">if</span> result <span class=\"k\">is None</span>:    <span class=\"c\"># correct</span>\n    ...\n<span class=\"k\">if</span> result == <span class=\"k\">None</span>:   <span class=\"c\"># works but wrong \u2014 == can be overridden</span>\n    ...</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 2. DATA TYPES \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"pyf-types\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>Data Types</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Numeric types</span>\nx = <span class=\"y\">42</span>          <span class=\"c\"># int \u2014 arbitrary precision (no overflow in Python)</span>\ny = <span class=\"y\">3.14</span>        <span class=\"c\"># float \u2014 IEEE 754 double (64-bit)</span>\nz = <span class=\"y\">3</span> + <span class=\"y\">4j</span>      <span class=\"c\"># complex \u2014 z.real=3.0, z.imag=4.0</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Float precision trap</span>\nprint(<span class=\"y\">0.1</span> + <span class=\"y\">0.2</span>)         <span class=\"c\"># 0.30000000000000004 \u2190 not 0.3!</span>\nprint(round(<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>+<span class=\"y\">0.2</span>, <span class=\"y\">10</span>))  <span class=\"c\"># use round() or decimal.Decimal for money</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Boolean \u2014 subclass of int!</span>\nprint(<span class=\"k\">True</span> + <span class=\"k\">True</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># 2</span>\nprint(<span class=\"k\">True</span> * <span class=\"y\">10</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># 10</span>\nprint(isinstance(<span class=\"k\">True</span>, int))  <span class=\"c\"># True \u2014 bool IS an int</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Strings \u2014 immutable sequences of Unicode codepoints</span>\ns = <span class=\"g\">\"hello\"</span>\ns[<span class=\"y\">0</span>] = <span class=\"g\">\"H\"</span>     <span class=\"c\"># TypeError: strings are immutable</span>\ns = <span class=\"g\">\"H\"</span> + s[<span class=\"y\">1</span>:]  <span class=\"c\"># creates a NEW string \u2014 \"Hello\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Type conversion \u2014 explicit casting</span>\nint(<span class=\"g\">\"42\"</span>)       <span class=\"c\"># 42    \u2014 string to int</span>\nint(<span class=\"y\">3.9</span>)        <span class=\"c\"># 3     \u2014 truncates (does NOT round)</span>\nfloat(<span class=\"g\">\"3.14\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># 3.14</span>\nstr(<span class=\"y\">42</span>)         <span class=\"c\"># \"42\"</span>\nbool(<span class=\"y\">0</span>)         <span class=\"c\"># False \u2014 falsy values: 0, 0.0, \"\", [], {}, None, False</span>\nbool(<span class=\"g\">\"hello\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># True  \u2014 non-empty string is truthy</span>\nlist(<span class=\"g\">\"abc\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># [\"a\", \"b\", \"c\"]</span>\ntuple([<span class=\"y\">1</span>,<span class=\"y\">2</span>])   <span class=\"c\"># (1, 2)</span></div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why Python integers never overflow</span>\n    <p>In C, an integer is stored in a fixed number of bits (32 or 64). When you exceed that, it wraps around \u2014 silent bugs. Python's <code>int</code> is a variable-precision object stored on the heap that grows as large as needed. <code>2 ** 1000</code> is a perfectly valid Python integer. The cost: Python integers are much slower than C integers, which is why NumPy arrays of fixed-width integers are dramatically faster for numeric computation.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 3. MUTABILITY \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"pyf-mutability\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Mutable vs Immutable \u2014 the most important distinction</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The analogy that makes this click</span>\n    <p>Think of an immutable object as a sealed envelope. To change what's inside, you must create a new envelope. An integer, string, or tuple is sealed \u2014 \"changing\" it always creates a new object.<br><br>\n    A mutable object is an open notebook. You can add pages, erase, rewrite \u2014 the notebook itself (its memory address) stays the same. A list, dict, or set is an open notebook.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 150\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">Mutable = same object changes. Immutable = new object created.</text>\n      <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"100\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Mutable (same object, new content)</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">list, dict, set, bytearray</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">a = [1,2,3]; id_before = id(a)</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">a.append(4)</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#0E9384\">id(a) == id_before  \u2190 True, same object</text>\n      <rect x=\"380\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"100\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">Immutable (new object created)</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">int, float, str, tuple, frozenset</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">s = \"hello\"; id_before = id(s)</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"116\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">s = s + \"!\"</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"132\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">id(s) != id_before  \u2190 new object!</text>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The mutable default argument trap \u2014 the #1 Python gotcha</span>\n    <p>Default argument values are evaluated <strong>once</strong> when the function is <strong>defined</strong>, not on each call. So a mutable default (like a list) is shared across every call that uses the default.</p>\n    <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># WRONG \u2014 the list is shared across ALL calls</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">add_item</span>(item, lst=[]):\n    lst.append(item)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> lst\n\nadd_item(<span class=\"y\">1</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [1]</span>\nadd_item(<span class=\"y\">2</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [1, 2]  \u2190 BUG! Should be [2]</span>\nadd_item(<span class=\"y\">3</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [1, 2, 3]  \u2190 still accumulating!</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># CORRECT \u2014 use None as sentinel, create fresh list each call</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">add_item</span>(item, lst=<span class=\"k\">None</span>):\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> lst <span class=\"k\">is None</span>:\n        lst = []\n    lst.append(item)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> lst</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why only immutables can be dict keys or set elements</span>\n    <p>When you use an object as a dict key, Python calls <code>hash(obj)</code> to compute its bucket position. If the object could change after being stored, its hash would change, and Python would lose track of where it is \u2014 your key would become unfindable. Immutable objects have stable hashes; mutable objects don't define <code>__hash__</code> by default (or set it to <code>None</code>) and raise <code>TypeError</code> if you try to hash them.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 4. OPERATORS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"pyf-operators\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Operators \u2014 all 7 types</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># 1. ARITHMETIC</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> + <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 13   \u2014 addition</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> - <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 7    \u2014 subtraction</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> * <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 30   \u2014 multiplication</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> / <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 3.333...  \u2014 true division, ALWAYS returns float</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> // <span class=\"y\">3</span>  <span class=\"c\"># 3    \u2014 floor division, rounds DOWN toward -infinity</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> % <span class=\"y\">3</span>   <span class=\"c\"># 1    \u2014 modulo (remainder)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">10</span> ** <span class=\"y\">3</span>  <span class=\"c\"># 1000 \u2014 exponentiation</span>\n-<span class=\"y\">7</span> // <span class=\"y\">2</span>   <span class=\"c\"># -4   \u2190 floor rounds DOWN, not toward zero!</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 2. COMPARISON \u2014 all return bool</span>\n<span class=\"y\">3</span> == <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span> != <span class=\"y\">4</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span> &lt; <span class=\"y\">4</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span> &lt;= <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span> &gt; <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span> &gt;= <span class=\"y\">3</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Chaining: 1 < x < 10 works in Python (not in most languages)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 3. LOGICAL \u2014 short-circuit evaluation</span>\n<span class=\"k\">True and False</span>   <span class=\"c\"># False \u2014 stops at first False</span>\n<span class=\"k\">True or False</span>    <span class=\"c\"># True  \u2014 stops at first True</span>\n<span class=\"k\">not True</span>         <span class=\"c\"># False</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Short-circuit returns the VALUE that determined the result:</span>\n<span class=\"y\">0</span> <span class=\"k\">or</span> <span class=\"g\">\"default\"</span>   <span class=\"c\"># \"default\" \u2014 0 is falsy, evaluates right side</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> <span class=\"k\">and</span> <span class=\"g\">\"yes\"</span>      <span class=\"c\"># \"yes\"    \u2014 5 is truthy, evaluates right side</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> <span class=\"k\">or</span> <span class=\"g\">\"never\"</span>     <span class=\"c\"># 5       \u2014 5 is truthy, stops immediately</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 4. ASSIGNMENT</span>\nx = <span class=\"y\">5</span>\nx += <span class=\"y\">1</span>  <span class=\"c\"># x = x + 1 = 6</span>\nx -= <span class=\"y\">1</span>  <span class=\"c\"># x = x - 1</span>\nx *= <span class=\"y\">2</span>  <span class=\"c\"># x = x * 2</span>\nx //= <span class=\"y\">2</span> <span class=\"c\"># x = x // 2</span>\nx **= <span class=\"y\">2</span> <span class=\"c\"># x = x ** 2</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 5. MEMBERSHIP</span>\n<span class=\"y\">3</span> <span class=\"k\">in</span> [<span class=\"y\">1</span>,<span class=\"y\">2</span>,<span class=\"y\">3</span>]      <span class=\"c\"># True  \u2014 O(n) for list!</span>\n<span class=\"y\">3</span> <span class=\"k\">in</span> {<span class=\"y\">1</span>,<span class=\"y\">2</span>,<span class=\"y\">3</span>}      <span class=\"c\"># True  \u2014 O(1) for set</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\"py\"</span> <span class=\"k\">in</span> <span class=\"g\">\"python\"</span>  <span class=\"c\"># True  \u2014 substring check</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\"x\"</span> <span class=\"k\">not in</span> [<span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>]  <span class=\"c\"># True</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 6. IDENTITY</span>\na <span class=\"k\">is</span> b       <span class=\"c\"># same object? (same id())</span>\na <span class=\"k\">is not</span> b  <span class=\"c\"># different objects?</span>\nx <span class=\"k\">is None</span>   <span class=\"c\"># always use is for None checks</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># 7. BITWISE \u2014 used in ML for masks, flags, hashing</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> &amp; <span class=\"y\">3</span>    <span class=\"c\"># 1    \u2014 AND:  0101 & 0011 = 0001</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> | <span class=\"y\">3</span>    <span class=\"c\"># 7    \u2014 OR:   0101 | 0011 = 0111</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> ^ <span class=\"y\">3</span>    <span class=\"c\"># 6    \u2014 XOR:  0101 ^ 0011 = 0110</span>\n~<span class=\"y\">5</span>       <span class=\"c\"># -6   \u2014 NOT:  -(n+1)</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> &lt;&lt; <span class=\"y\">1</span>  <span class=\"c\"># 10   \u2014 left shift = multiply by 2</span>\n<span class=\"y\">5</span> &gt;&gt; <span class=\"y\">1</span>  <span class=\"c\"># 2    \u2014 right shift = floor divide by 2</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># WALRUS OPERATOR := (Python 3.8+)</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Assigns AND returns value \u2014 use to avoid evaluating twice</span>\n<span class=\"k\">while</span> chunk := f.read(<span class=\"y\">1024</span>):    <span class=\"c\"># read AND check in one step</span>\n    process(chunk)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Also useful in comprehensions:</span>\nresults = [y := compute(x), y**<span class=\"y\">2</span>, y**<span class=\"y\">3</span>]  <span class=\"c\"># compute once, use three times</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 5. CONTROL FLOW \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"pyf-control\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Control Flow</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># if / elif / else</span>\nscore = <span class=\"y\">85</span>\n<span class=\"k\">if</span> score >= <span class=\"y\">90</span>:\n    grade = <span class=\"g\">\"A\"</span>\n<span class=\"k\">elif</span> score >= <span class=\"y\">80</span>:\n    grade = <span class=\"g\">\"B\"</span>\n<span class=\"k\">else</span>:\n    grade = <span class=\"g\">\"C\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Ternary expression</span>\ngrade = <span class=\"g\">\"pass\"</span> <span class=\"k\">if</span> score >= <span class=\"y\">60</span> <span class=\"k\">else</span> <span class=\"g\">\"fail\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># for loop \u2014 iterates over any iterable</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">5</span>):              <span class=\"c\"># 0, 1, 2, 3, 4</span>\n    print(i)\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> i, val <span class=\"k\">in</span> enumerate([<span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>,<span class=\"g\">\"b\"</span>]):  <span class=\"c\"># (0, \"a\"), (1, \"b\")</span>\n    print(i, val)\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> k, v <span class=\"k\">in</span> {<span class=\"g\">\"x\"</span>:<span class=\"y\">1</span>}.items():     <span class=\"c\"># dict iteration</span>\n    print(k, v)\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> a, b <span class=\"k\">in</span> zip([<span class=\"y\">1</span>,<span class=\"y\">2</span>], [<span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>,<span class=\"g\">\"b\"</span>]):  <span class=\"c\"># pairs from two lists</span>\n    print(a, b)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># break / continue / for...else</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">10</span>):\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> i == <span class=\"y\">3</span>: <span class=\"k\">continue</span>  <span class=\"c\"># skip iteration</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> i == <span class=\"y\">7</span>: <span class=\"k\">break</span>    <span class=\"c\"># exit loop entirely</span>\n<span class=\"k\">else</span>:\n    <span class=\"c\"># Runs ONLY if loop completed without hitting break</span>\n    print(<span class=\"g\">\"completed\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># \u2190 will NOT print here (we broke at 7)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Classic use of for...else: search</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> item <span class=\"k\">in</span> collection:\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> item.matches(target):\n        found = item\n        <span class=\"k\">break</span>\n<span class=\"k\">else</span>:\n    found = <span class=\"k\">None</span>  <span class=\"c\"># no break = not found</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># while loop</span>\nn = <span class=\"y\">10</span>\n<span class=\"k\">while</span> n > <span class=\"y\">0</span>:\n    n -= <span class=\"y\">1</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Pattern matching (Python 3.10+) \u2014 structural switch</span>\n<span class=\"k\">match</span> command:\n    <span class=\"k\">case</span> <span class=\"g\">\"quit\"</span>:\n        exit()\n    <span class=\"k\">case</span> <span class=\"g\">\"help\"</span> | <span class=\"g\">\"?\"</span>:           <span class=\"c\"># OR pattern</span>\n        show_help()\n    <span class=\"k\">case</span> {<span class=\"g\">\"action\"</span>: action, <span class=\"g\">\"value\"</span>: v}:  <span class=\"c\"># destructure dict</span>\n        handle(action, v)\n    <span class=\"k\">case</span> [first, *rest]:           <span class=\"c\"># destructure list</span>\n        print(first, rest)\n    <span class=\"k\">case</span> _:                        <span class=\"c\"># default</span>\n        print(<span class=\"g\">\"unknown\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 6. FUNCTIONS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"pyf-functions\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Functions \u2014 the engine of abstraction</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why functions matter more than they seem</span>\n    <p>A function is not just \"reusable code\". In Python, functions are <strong>first-class objects</strong> \u2014 they can be assigned to variables, passed as arguments, returned from other functions, and stored in data structures. This is what makes decorators, callbacks, and higher-order programming possible.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Basic function with type hints and docstring</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">greet</span>(name: str, greeting: str = <span class=\"g\">\"Hello\"</span>) -> str:\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Return a greeting string. Type hints are documentation + tooling help.\"\"\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> f<span class=\"g\">\"{greeting}, {name}!\"</span>\n\ngreet(<span class=\"g\">\"Aman\"</span>)                     <span class=\"c\"># positional \u2014 \"Hello, Aman!\"</span>\ngreet(name=<span class=\"g\">\"Aman\"</span>, greeting=<span class=\"g\">\"Hey\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># keyword arguments</span>\ngreet(<span class=\"g\">\"Aman\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"Hey\"</span>)               <span class=\"c\"># both positional</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># *args \u2014 variable positional arguments (arrives as a TUPLE)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">total</span>(*args):\n    print(type(args))  <span class=\"c\"># &lt;class 'tuple'&gt;</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> sum(args)\ntotal(<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">4</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 10</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># **kwargs \u2014 variable keyword arguments (arrives as a DICT)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">config</span>(**kwargs):\n    print(type(kwargs))  <span class=\"c\"># &lt;class 'dict'&gt;</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> k, v <span class=\"k\">in</span> kwargs.items():\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"{k}={v}\"</span>)\nconfig(lr=<span class=\"y\">0.001</span>, epochs=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Parameter ORDER: positional \u2192 *args \u2192 keyword-only \u2192 **kwargs</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">f</span>(a, b, *args, key=<span class=\"g\">\"default\"</span>, **kwargs): ...\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Unpacking when CALLING a function</span>\nnums = [<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>]\nprint(*nums)                  <span class=\"c\"># same as print(1, 2, 3)</span>\nsettings = {<span class=\"g\">\"lr\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">0.01</span>}\ntrain(**settings)              <span class=\"c\"># same as train(lr=0.01)</span></div>\n\n  <h3>Scope \u2014 LEGB rule</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">LEGB \u2014 how Python resolves a name</span>\n    <p>When you use a variable name, Python searches in this order: <strong>L</strong>ocal (current function) \u2192 <strong>E</strong>nclosing (outer functions) \u2192 <strong>G</strong>lobal (module level) \u2192 <strong>B</strong>uilt-in (Python builtins like <code>len</code>, <code>print</code>). It stops at the first match.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\">x = <span class=\"g\">\"global\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">outer</span>():\n    x = <span class=\"g\">\"enclosing\"</span>          <span class=\"c\"># enclosing scope</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">inner</span>():\n        <span class=\"k\">nonlocal</span> x             <span class=\"c\"># reach into enclosing scope</span>\n        x = <span class=\"g\">\"inner modified\"</span>   <span class=\"c\"># modifies outer's x</    </span>\n\n    inner()\n    print(x)                   <span class=\"c\"># \"inner modified\"</span>\n\nouter()\nprint(x)                       <span class=\"c\"># \"global\" \u2014 unchanged</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">reset</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">global</span> x                  <span class=\"c\"># reach into module scope</span>\n    x = <span class=\"g\">\"reset\"</span>\n\nreset()\nprint(x)                       <span class=\"c\"># \"reset\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Lambda \u2014 anonymous single-expression function</span>\nsquare = <span class=\"k\">lambda</span> x: x ** <span class=\"y\">2</span>\nsorted_data = sorted(people, key=<span class=\"k\">lambda</span> p: p[<span class=\"g\">\"age\"</span>], reverse=<span class=\"k\">True</span>)</div>\n\n  <h2 id=\"pyf-qa\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\"><h3>Answer before revealing</h3><button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button></div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the difference between is and ==?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\"><code>==</code> checks value equality \u2014 it calls <code>__eq__</code> on the objects. <code>is</code> checks identity \u2014 whether two names point to the exact same object in memory (same <code>id()</code>). A classic trap: <code>[1,2] == [1,2]</code> is True (same values), but <code>[1,2] is [1,2]</code> is False (different list objects). Always use <code>is</code> for <code>None</code> checks because <code>==</code> can be overridden by <code>__eq__</code>.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Mutable vs immutable \u2014 give examples and explain why it matters.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Mutable objects (list, dict, set) can be changed in place \u2014 their content changes but the object's identity stays the same. Immutable objects (int, float, str, tuple) cannot be changed \u2014 any \"change\" creates a new object. Why it matters: (1) Aliasing \u2014 two variables pointing to the same mutable object means modifying via one variable changes what the other sees. (2) Hashability \u2014 only immutable objects can be dict keys or set elements, because their hash must never change. (3) Thread safety \u2014 immutable objects are inherently safe to share across threads.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Explain the mutable default argument trap.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Default arguments are evaluated once when the function is defined, not on each call. So <code>def f(lst=[])</code> creates a single list object at definition time. Every call that uses the default shares this same list \u2014 appending to it persists across calls. The fix: use <code>None</code> as the default and create a fresh list inside the function body: <code>if lst is None: lst = []</code>. This is one of the most common Python interview questions.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What does short-circuit evaluation mean and why is it useful?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Python evaluates <code>and</code> and <code>or</code> expressions lazily \u2014 it stops as soon as the result is determined. <code>A and B</code>: if A is falsy, B is never evaluated (returns A). If A is truthy, returns B. <code>A or B</code>: if A is truthy, B is never evaluated (returns A). If A is falsy, returns B. Practical uses: <code>result = value or \"default\"</code> (fallback), <code>obj and obj.method()</code> (null-safe method call), <code>condition and expensive_function()</code> (avoid expensive call when not needed).</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the LEGB rule?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">LEGB is the name resolution order Python uses when looking up a variable: Local (the current function's scope) \u2192 Enclosing (any outer functions' scopes, from innermost outward) \u2192 Global (the module level) \u2192 Built-in (Python's built-in names like <code>len</code>, <code>print</code>). Python searches each scope in that order and stops at the first match. <code>nonlocal</code> explicitly reaches into the Enclosing scope to modify a variable. <code>global</code> explicitly reaches into the Global scope.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What does *args and **kwargs actually do inside the function?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\"><code>*args</code> collects any extra positional arguments into a <strong>tuple</strong> inside the function. <code>**kwargs</code> collects any extra keyword arguments into a <strong>dict</strong>. They can also be used when calling a function: <code>f(*my_list)</code> unpacks the list into positional arguments, and <code>f(**my_dict)</code> unpacks the dict into keyword arguments. The names <code>args</code> and <code>kwargs</code> are just conventions \u2014 the <code>*</code> and <code>**</code> are what actually matter.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "py_ds": "<main>\n  <h1>Data Structures</h1>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-ds\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Built-in Structures</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">list, tuple, set, dict \u2014 O() complexity</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-exceptions\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Exception Handling</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">try/except, custom exceptions, logging</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-files\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">File Handling</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">txt, csv, json, parquet, pickle, yaml</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-modules\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Modules & Packages</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">imports, venv, pip, poetry</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n    <h2>Revision</h2>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>list vs tuple \u2014 the real tradeoff:</strong> list is mutable, dynamically resized, and cannot be a dict key. tuple is immutable, slightly faster, and hashable \u2014 so it can be a dict key or set element. Use tuple when the data shouldn't change and when you need it as a key. The immutability isn't just a restriction; it's a guarantee the rest of your code can rely on.</li>\n      <li><strong>set and dict are both hash tables:</strong> membership testing (<code>x in s</code>) is O(1) average for both, versus O(n) for a list. The single most common interview optimisation is swapping a list for a set when you're repeatedly checking membership \u2014 it collapses an O(n\u00b2) loop to O(n). Keys must be hashable (immutable), which is why you can't use a list as a dict key.</li>\n      <li><strong>defaultdict eliminates the KeyError dance:</strong> <code>defaultdict(list)</code> auto-creates an empty list on first access to a missing key, so you can write <code>d[k].append(x)</code> without checking if k exists first. <code>Counter</code> is a specialised dict for counting \u2014 <code>Counter(items).most_common(k)</code> is the canonical \"top-k frequency\" one-liner.</li>\n      <li><strong>Shallow vs deep copy \u2014 where bugs hide:</strong> <code>lst.copy()</code> or <code>lst[:]</code> creates a new outer list but the inner objects are still shared references. Mutating a nested list inside the copy mutates the original too. <code>copy.deepcopy()</code> recursively copies everything. This bites people with lists of lists and dicts of dicts.</li>\n      <li><strong>Comprehensions are faster, not just shorter:</strong> <code>[x**2 for x in data if x%2==0]</code> runs faster than an equivalent for-loop with append because the iteration happens in C, not Python bytecode. But nest more than two levels and readability collapses \u2014 at that point use a generator or a named function.</li>\n      <li><strong>String immutability trap:</strong> every string operation creates a new string. Building a string by repeated concatenation in a loop (<code>s += char</code>) is O(n\u00b2) because each += copies the whole string. Use <code>''.join(list_of_strings)</code> instead \u2014 it's O(n) and the standard fix.</li>\n      <li><strong>Exception flow \u2014 else and finally:</strong> the <code>else</code> block runs only if no exception was raised in the try. <code>finally</code> always runs, even if an exception propagates or you return early \u2014 use it for cleanup (closing files, releasing locks). Custom exceptions should subclass Exception and carry context in <code>__init__</code> so callers can handle them specifically.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n\n<h2 id=\"py-ds\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Data Structures</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Python's Four Built-in Data Structures</span>\n    <p>Python gives you four core containers, each making a different trade-off: <strong>list</strong> \u2014 ordered sequence, mutable, allows duplicates. <strong>tuple</strong> \u2014 ordered sequence, immutable, hashable. <strong>set</strong> \u2014 unordered, unique values only, O(1) membership test. <strong>dict</strong> \u2014 key\u2192value mapping, ordered (Python 3.7+), O(1) lookup. Every other data structure in Python is built on top of these four.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 four different kinds of storage</span>\n    <p>A <strong>list</strong> is a shopping basket \u2014 you put things in, they stay in order, you can have two identical items, you can add and remove freely.<br>\n    A <strong>tuple</strong> is a sealed envelope \u2014 once you put things in, they're fixed. The immutability is a guarantee, not just a restriction.<br>\n    A <strong>set</strong> is a stamp collection \u2014 every stamp is unique, you can instantly check \"do I have this stamp?\", but you can't ask \"what's the third stamp?\".<br>\n    A <strong>dict</strong> is a filing cabinet with labelled folders \u2014 find anything by its label in constant time, regardless of how many folders exist.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The O(n) membership trap \u2014 the most common Python performance mistake</span>\n    <p><code>x in list</code> scans from index 0 every time \u2014 O(n). In a loop over 10,000 items each checking a list of 10,000 elements, that's 100 million comparisons. <code>x in set</code> is O(1) \u2014 hash lookup. Converting the list to a set before the loop is the single most common Python O(n\u00b2) \u2192 O(n) fix. The cost: O(n) to build the set, O(1) forever after.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 160\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">Choosing the right data structure</text>\n      <g text-anchor=\"middle\">\n        <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"125\" height=\"105\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">list</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">ordered, mutable</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">duplicates OK</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(1) append</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(n) search</text>\n        <text x=\"82\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">default sequence</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"160\" y=\"38\" width=\"125\" height=\"105\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#F4EFFE\" stroke=\"#D9C8FA\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">tuple</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">ordered, immutable</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">hashable (dict key)</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">faster than list</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">less memory</text>\n        <text x=\"222\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">fixed data / coords</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"300\" y=\"38\" width=\"125\" height=\"105\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">set</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">unordered, mutable</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">no duplicates</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(1) lookup</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(1) add/remove</text>\n        <text x=\"362\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#0E9384\">dedup + membership</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"440\" y=\"38\" width=\"240\" height=\"105\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#FEF5E7\" stroke=\"#F4D49A\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"10.5\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#C2710C\">dict</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">key\u2192value, ordered (3.7+)</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"95\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">O(1) get/set/delete</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"110\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">keys must be hashable</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"125\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">no duplicate keys</text>\n        <text x=\"560\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#C2710C\">configs, caching, JSON</text>\n      </g>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <h3>Lists</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Creation and basic operations</span>\nlst = [<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">4</span>, <span class=\"y\">5</span>]\nlst.append(<span class=\"y\">6</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># [1,2,3,4,5,6]</span>\nlst.insert(<span class=\"y\">0</span>, <span class=\"y\">0</span>)       <span class=\"c\"># [0,1,2,3,4,5,6]</span>\nlst.pop()              <span class=\"c\"># removes + returns last: 6</span>\nlst.pop(<span class=\"y\">0</span>)             <span class=\"c\"># removes + returns index 0: 0</span>\nlst.remove(<span class=\"y\">3</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># removes first occurrence of value 3</span>\nlst.sort()             <span class=\"c\"># in-place sort</span>\nsorted(lst)            <span class=\"c\"># returns new sorted list</span>\nlst.reverse()          <span class=\"c\"># in-place reverse</span>\nlen(lst)               <span class=\"c\"># length</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Slicing \u2014 [start:stop:step]  (stop is exclusive)</span>\nlst = [<span class=\"y\">0</span>,<span class=\"y\">1</span>,<span class=\"y\">2</span>,<span class=\"y\">3</span>,<span class=\"y\">4</span>,<span class=\"y\">5</span>]\nlst[<span class=\"y\">1</span>:<span class=\"y\">4</span>]       <span class=\"c\"># [1, 2, 3]</span>\nlst[:<span class=\"y\">3</span>]        <span class=\"c\"># [0, 1, 2]</span>\nlst[<span class=\"y\">3</span>:]        <span class=\"c\"># [3, 4, 5]</span>\nlst[::-<span class=\"y\">1</span>]      <span class=\"c\"># [5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0]  \u2014 reverse</span>\nlst[::2]       <span class=\"c\"># [0, 2, 4]            \u2014 every other</span>\nlst[-<span class=\"y\">2</span>:]       <span class=\"c\"># [4, 5]               \u2014 last 2</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># List comprehensions \u2014 the Pythonic way</span>\nsquares   = [x**<span class=\"y\">2</span> <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">10</span>)]\nevens     = [x <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">20</span>) <span class=\"k\">if</span> x % <span class=\"y\">2</span> == <span class=\"y\">0</span>]\nmatrix    = [[i*j <span class=\"k\">for</span> j <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">3</span>)] <span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">3</span>)]  <span class=\"c\"># nested</span>\nflattened = [x <span class=\"k\">for</span> row <span class=\"k\">in</span> matrix <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> row]           <span class=\"c\"># flatten</span></div>\n\n  <h3>Dictionaries</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Creation and operations</span>\nd = {<span class=\"g\">\"name\"</span>: <span class=\"g\">\"Aman\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"age\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">30</span>}\nd[<span class=\"g\">\"city\"</span>] = <span class=\"g\">\"Noida\"</span>         <span class=\"c\"># add/update</span>\nd.get(<span class=\"g\">\"salary\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">0</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># safe get with default \u2014 no KeyError</span>\nd.pop(<span class=\"g\">\"age\"</span>)               <span class=\"c\"># remove and return value</span>\nd.keys()                   <span class=\"c\"># dict_keys view</span>\nd.values()                 <span class=\"c\"># dict_values view</span>\nd.items()                  <span class=\"c\"># dict_items view \u2014 (key, value) pairs</span>\nd.update({<span class=\"g\">\"x\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"y\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">2</span>}) <span class=\"c\"># merge another dict in</span>\n{**d, <span class=\"g\">\"z\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">3</span>}              <span class=\"c\"># merge with spread (creates new dict)</span>\nd | {<span class=\"g\">\"z\"</span>: <span class=\"y\">3</span>}               <span class=\"c\"># merge operator (Python 3.9+)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Dict comprehension</span>\nsquares = {x: x**<span class=\"y\">2</span> <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">5</span>)}\nfiltered = {k: v <span class=\"k\">for</span> k, v <span class=\"k\">in</span> d.items() <span class=\"k\">if</span> v > <span class=\"y\">10</span>}\n\n<span class=\"c\"># defaultdict \u2014 never KeyError on missing keys</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> collections <span class=\"k\">import</span> defaultdict\ndd = defaultdict(list)\ndd[<span class=\"g\">\"tags\"</span>].append(<span class=\"g\">\"python\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># auto-creates empty list if key missing</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Counter \u2014 count occurrences</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> collections <span class=\"k\">import</span> Counter\nc = Counter([<span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"b\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"c\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>])\nc.most_common(<span class=\"y\">2</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [(\"a\", 3), (\"b\", 1)]</span></div>\n\n  <h3>Sets</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\">a = {<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">4</span>}\nb = {<span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">4</span>, <span class=\"y\">5</span>, <span class=\"y\">6</span>}\na | b       <span class=\"c\"># {1,2,3,4,5,6}  union</span>\na &amp; b       <span class=\"c\"># {3, 4}          intersection</span>\na - b       <span class=\"c\"># {1, 2}          difference</span>\na ^ b       <span class=\"c\"># {1,2,5,6}       symmetric difference (in one but not both)</span>\na.issubset(b)    <span class=\"c\"># is every element of a in b?</span>\na.issuperset(b)  <span class=\"c\"># is every element of b in a?</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Deduplication pattern</span>\nunique = list(set([<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>]))  <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [1, 2, 3] (order not guaranteed)</span></div>\n\n  <h3>Strings</h3>\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Strings are immutable sequences of characters</span>\ns = <span class=\"g\">\"Hello, World!\"</span>\ns.upper()          <span class=\"c\"># \"HELLO, WORLD!\"</span>\ns.lower()          <span class=\"c\"># \"hello, world!\"</span>\ns.strip()          <span class=\"c\"># remove leading/trailing whitespace</span>\ns.split(<span class=\"g\">\",\"</span>)       <span class=\"c\"># [\"Hello\", \" World!\"]</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\",\"</span>.join([<span class=\"g\">\"a\"</span>,<span class=\"g\">\"b\"</span>]) <span class=\"c\"># \"a,b\"</span>\ns.replace(<span class=\"g\">\"l\"</span>,<span class=\"g\">\"L\"</span>) <span class=\"c\"># \"HeLLo, WorLd!\"</span>\ns.startswith(<span class=\"g\">\"He\"</span>) <span class=\"c\"># True</span>\ns.find(<span class=\"g\">\"World\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># 7 (index) or -1 if not found</span>\ns[<span class=\"y\">7</span>:<span class=\"y\">12</span>]            <span class=\"c\"># \"World\" \u2014 slicing works on strings too</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># String formatting</span>\nname, score = <span class=\"g\">\"Aman\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">95.5</span>\nf<span class=\"g\">\"{name} scored {score:.1f}%\"</span>           <span class=\"c\"># f-string (fastest, most readable)</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\"{} scored {:.1f}%\"</span>.format(name, score) <span class=\"c\"># .format()</span>\n<span class=\"g\">\"%s scored %.1f%%\"</span> % (name, score)      <span class=\"c\"># % formatting (old style)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Regex</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> re\npattern = re.compile(<span class=\"g\">r\"\\d+\"</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># compile for reuse</span>\nre.findall(<span class=\"g\">r\"\\d+\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"abc123def456\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 [\"123\", \"456\"]</span>\nre.sub(<span class=\"g\">r\"\\s+\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\" \"</span>, text)            <span class=\"c\"># replace multiple spaces with one</span>\nre.match(<span class=\"g\">r\"^\\d{4}\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"2024-01-01\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># match at start</span>\nre.search(<span class=\"g\">r\"\\d{4}\"</span>, text)            <span class=\"c\"># match anywhere</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 6. EXCEPTIONS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-exceptions\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Exception Handling</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Exception Handling</span>\n    <p>A control flow mechanism for handling errors without crashing. Python uses <code>try/except/else/finally</code>: code in <code>try</code> runs first. If an exception occurs, the matching <code>except</code> block runs. <code>else</code> runs only if <em>no</em> exception occurred. <code>finally</code> always runs \u2014 exception or not. This ordering matters: <code>else</code> is for \"success path only\", <code>finally</code> is for cleanup that must always happen.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 a bank transaction</span>\n    <p>You attempt a transfer (try). If it fails \u2014 account frozen, wrong details (except) \u2014 you handle it. If it succeeds (else) \u2014 you log the confirmation. Whether it succeeded or failed, you always release the database connection (finally). The finally block is the code that must run regardless of what happened \u2014 it's the cleanup, the resource release, the door you always close on the way out.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">except Exception vs bare except \u2014 never use bare except</span>\n    <p><code>except:</code> with no type catches <em>everything</em> \u2014 including <code>SystemExit</code>, <code>KeyboardInterrupt</code>, and <code>GeneratorExit</code>. Your Ctrl+C now does nothing. Your program can't be killed normally. Use <code>except Exception:</code> at minimum. Better: catch the specific exception you expect (<code>except ValueError:</code>, <code>except FileNotFoundError:</code>). The more specific, the better \u2014 broad catches hide bugs.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why this matters in ML systems</span>\n    <p>Production ML pipelines fail constantly \u2014 network timeouts, corrupt data, API rate limits, out-of-memory errors. Unhandled exceptions crash your entire pipeline at 2 AM. Good exception handling means the system logs the error, handles it gracefully, and keeps running.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Basic try/except/else/finally</span>\n<span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n    result = <span class=\"y\">10</span> / x          <span class=\"c\"># might raise ZeroDivisionError</span>\n    data = json.loads(s)      <span class=\"c\"># might raise JSONDecodeError</span>\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> ZeroDivisionError:\n    print(<span class=\"g\">\"division by zero\"</span>)\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> (ValueError, TypeError) <span class=\"k\">as</span> e:\n    print(f<span class=\"g\">\"value/type error: {e}\"</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># multiple exceptions</span>\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> Exception <span class=\"k\">as</span> e:\n    print(f<span class=\"g\">\"unexpected: {e}\"</span>)         <span class=\"c\"># catch-all (use sparingly)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">else</span>:\n    print(<span class=\"g\">\"no exception occurred\"</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># runs ONLY if no exception</span>\n<span class=\"k\">finally</span>:\n    cleanup()                          <span class=\"c\"># ALWAYS runs (even if exception)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Raising exceptions</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">divide</span>(a, b):\n    <span class=\"k\">if</span> b == <span class=\"y\">0</span>:\n        <span class=\"k\">raise</span> ValueError(<span class=\"g\">\"b cannot be zero\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> a / b\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Re-raising \u2014 preserve original traceback</span>\n<span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n    risky()\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> SomeError <span class=\"k\">as</span> e:\n    log(e)\n    <span class=\"k\">raise</span>   <span class=\"c\"># re-raise the same exception</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Custom exception classes</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">DataValidationError</span>(ValueError):\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Raised when input data fails validation.\"\"\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, field: str, message: str):\n        self.field = field\n        super().__init__(f<span class=\"g\">\"Field '{field}': {message}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"k\">raise</span> DataValidationError(<span class=\"g\">\"age\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"must be positive\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Exception hierarchy (most specific first in except blocks)</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># BaseException</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#   \u2514\u2500\u2500 Exception</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#         \u251c\u2500\u2500 ValueError, TypeError, KeyError, IndexError</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#         \u251c\u2500\u2500 OSError \u2192 FileNotFoundError, PermissionError</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#         \u2514\u2500\u2500 RuntimeError, StopIteration, ...</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Logging exceptions (production pattern)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> logging\nlogging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO)\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n<span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n    process()\n<span class=\"k\">except</span> Exception:\n    logger.exception(<span class=\"g\">\"Processing failed\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># logs full traceback automatically</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 7. FILE HANDLING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-files\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>File Handling</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 File Handling</span>\n    <p>Reading from and writing to files on disk. Python's built-in <code>open()</code> handles text files. The standard library and ecosystem handle every format: <code>csv</code> module for CSV, <code>json</code> for JSON, <code>pickle</code> for Python objects, <code>pandas</code> for parquet/excel. Always use <code>with open()</code> \u2014 the context manager guarantees the file is closed even if an exception occurs mid-read.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Text mode vs binary mode \u2014 a silent data corruption trap</span>\n    <p>Opening a file in text mode (<code>open('f', 'r')</code>) applies platform-specific newline translation: on Windows, <code>\\r\\n</code> becomes <code>\\n</code>. On Mac/Linux, no change. If you read a binary file (image, pickle, parquet) in text mode, the translations corrupt the bytes. Rule: text files \u2192 text mode. Everything else \u2192 binary mode (<code>'rb'</code>, <code>'wb'</code>). Always specify encoding for text: <code>open('f', 'r', encoding='utf-8')</code>.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Text files</span>\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"data.txt\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"r\"</span>, encoding=<span class=\"g\">\"utf-8\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    content = f.read()           <span class=\"c\"># whole file as string</span>\n    lines = f.readlines()        <span class=\"c\"># list of lines</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> line <span class=\"k\">in</span> f:              <span class=\"c\"># line-by-line (memory efficient)</span>\n        process(line.strip())\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"output.txt\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"w\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:   <span class=\"c\"># \"w\"=write, \"a\"=append</span>\n    f.write(<span class=\"g\">\"hello\\n\"</span>)\n    f.writelines([<span class=\"g\">\"line1\\n\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"line2\\n\"</span>])\n\n<span class=\"c\"># CSV \u2014 use pandas for real work, csv module for lightweight</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> csv\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"data.csv\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    reader = csv.DictReader(f)   <span class=\"c\"># each row \u2192 dict with column names</span>\n    rows = list(reader)\n\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pandas <span class=\"k\">as</span> pd\ndf = pd.read_csv(<span class=\"g\">\"data.csv\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># the production way</span>\ndf.to_csv(<span class=\"g\">\"out.csv\"</span>, index=<span class=\"k\">False</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># JSON</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> json\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"config.json\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    config = json.load(f)        <span class=\"c\"># file \u2192 Python dict</span>\njson_str = json.dumps(config, indent=<span class=\"y\">2</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># dict \u2192 string</span>\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"out.json\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"w\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    json.dump(config, f, indent=<span class=\"y\">2</span>)       <span class=\"c\"># dict \u2192 file</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Parquet \u2014 columnar storage for large ML datasets</span>\ndf = pd.read_parquet(<span class=\"g\">\"data.parquet\"</span>)\ndf.to_parquet(<span class=\"g\">\"out.parquet\"</span>, index=<span class=\"k\">False</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Pickle \u2014 serialize any Python object</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pickle\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"model.pkl\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"wb\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:   <span class=\"c\"># \"wb\" = write binary</span>\n    pickle.dump(model, f)\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"model.pkl\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"rb\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    model = pickle.load(f)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># YAML \u2014 config files (requires PyYAML)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> yaml\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"config.yaml\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> f:\n    config = yaml.safe_load(f)   <span class=\"c\"># always use safe_load, not load</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># pathlib \u2014 modern path handling (preferred over os.path)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> pathlib <span class=\"k\">import</span> Path\np = Path(<span class=\"g\">\"data\"</span>) / <span class=\"g\">\"raw\"</span> / <span class=\"g\">\"file.csv\"</span>\np.exists()            <span class=\"c\"># True/False</span>\np.mkdir(parents=<span class=\"k\">True</span>, exist_ok=<span class=\"k\">True</span>)\nlist(p.parent.glob(<span class=\"g\">\"*.csv\"</span>))   <span class=\"c\"># all CSV files</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 8. MODULES \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-modules\"><span class=\"num\">08</span>Modules & Packages</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Modules and Packages</span>\n    <p>A <strong>module</strong> is any <code>.py</code> file. A <strong>package</strong> is a directory containing an <code>__init__.py</code> file and other modules. Importing a module executes its top-level code once and caches the result in <code>sys.modules</code> \u2014 subsequent imports return the cached version. A <strong>virtual environment</strong> is an isolated Python installation with its own set of packages, so project A and project B can use different versions of the same library without conflict.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why virtual environments exist \u2014 the dependency hell problem</span>\n    <p>Project A needs numpy 1.24. Project B needs numpy 2.0. They can't both be installed globally \u2014 one overwrites the other. A virtual environment is a separate Python installation for each project. Project A runs in env_A (numpy 1.24). Project B runs in env_B (numpy 2.0). They never see each other. Without this, every new project risks breaking every existing project on your machine.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Import styles</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> math                      <span class=\"c\"># import module</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> math <span class=\"k\">import</span> sqrt, pi        <span class=\"c\"># import specific names</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> math <span class=\"k\">import</span> *               <span class=\"c\"># import all (avoid \u2014 pollutes namespace)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np               <span class=\"c\"># alias</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> . <span class=\"k\">import</span> utils              <span class=\"c\"># relative import (inside a package)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># __name__ \u2014 module's name when imported vs run directly</span>\n<span class=\"k\">if</span> __name__ == <span class=\"g\">\"__main__\"</span>:\n    main()   <span class=\"c\"># only runs when file is executed directly, not when imported</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Package structure</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># myproject/</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#   __init__.py     \u2190 makes it a package, can define public API</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#   models/</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#     __init__.py</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#     transformer.py</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#   utils/</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#     __init__.py</span>\n<span class=\"c\">#     preprocessing.py</span></div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Virtual environments \u2014 isolate project dependencies</span>\npython -m venv .venv           <span class=\"c\"># create</span>\nsource .venv/bin/activate      <span class=\"c\"># activate (Linux/Mac)</span>\n.venv\\Scripts\\activate         <span class=\"c\"># activate (Windows)</span>\npip install -r requirements.txt\n\n<span class=\"c\"># requirements.txt</span>\nnumpy==1.26.0\npandas>=2.0.0\ntorch>=2.1.0\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Poetry \u2014 modern dependency management</span>\npoetry new myproject           <span class=\"c\"># create project</span>\npoetry add numpy pandas        <span class=\"c\"># add dependencies</span>\npoetry add --group dev pytest  <span class=\"c\"># dev-only dependency</span>\npoetry install                 <span class=\"c\"># install all</span>\npoetry run python main.py      <span class=\"c\"># run in poetry env</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 9. OOP \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  \n\n</main>",
  "py_oop": "<main>\n  <h1>Object-Oriented Programming</h1>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"oop-basics\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Class & Object</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Blueprint vs instance, __init__, self</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"oop-attrs\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Attributes & Methods</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Instance, class, static \u2014 and when to use each</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"oop-pillars\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">The Four Pillars</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Inheritance, Polymorphism, Encapsulation, Abstraction</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"oop-magic\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Magic / Dunder Methods</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">__str__, __repr__, __eq__, __add__ and more</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"oop-overload\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Operator Overloading</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Redefine +, -, ==, < for custom objects</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"oop-comp\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">06</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Composition vs Inheritance</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">is-a vs has-a \u2014 when to use which</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"oop-property\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">07</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">@property & Access Control</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Getters, setters, private vs protected</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"oop-mro\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">08</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">MRO & Multiple Inheritance</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">C3 linearisation, diamond problem</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n    <h2>Revision</h2>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>Class = blueprint. Object = instance.</strong> One blueprint, many independent houses. Changing one house doesn't change others.</li>\n      <li><strong>__init__</strong> runs automatically when an object is created. Never call it manually. It is a method (function inside a class).</li>\n      <li><strong>self</strong> = the word \"my\" \u2014 each object refers to its own data. Python passes self automatically; you never pass it when calling.</li>\n      <li><strong>Inheritance = is-a.</strong> Doctor is-a Staff \u2192 inherit. Always call super().__init__() or parent attributes are never set.</li>\n      <li><strong>Polymorphism:</strong> same method name, different behaviour per class. Python decides at runtime \u2014 this is called dynamic dispatch.</li>\n      <li><strong>Encapsulation = protect DATA.</strong> Double underscore makes it private. Use getters/setters to validate before changing.</li>\n      <li><strong>Abstraction = hide COMPLEXITY.</strong> ABC + @abstractmethod forces subclasses to implement the method \u2014 acts as a contract.</li>\n      <li><strong>Encapsulation vs Abstraction:</strong> Encapsulation hides data. Abstraction hides implementation. Most common interview trap.</li>\n      <li><strong>__repr__</strong> is for developers (recreate the object). <strong>__str__</strong> is for end users (readable output). If you define only one, define __repr__.</li>\n      <li><strong>Composition = has-a.</strong> Car HAS an Engine. Preferred over inheritance when the relationship might change or you want loose coupling.</li>\n      <li><strong>MRO:</strong> Method Resolution Order \u2014 how Python resolves which class's method to call in multiple inheritance. Check with ClassName.__mro__.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 1. CLASS & OBJECT \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"oop-basics\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Class & Object \u2014 blueprint vs instance</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why OOP exists at all</span>\n    <p>Without OOP, data and behavior are disconnected. Imagine managing 500 patients with loose variables \u2014 <code>patient1_name</code>, <code>patient2_name</code>... That's 2,500 variables with no structure. One typo breaks everything silently.<br><br>\n    OOP groups related data and behavior into one unit called a class. The patient's name, age, diagnosis, and methods like <code>admit()</code>, <code>discharge()</code> all live together in one place.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Class and Object</span>\n    <p>A <strong>class</strong> is a blueprint that defines what a type of thing looks like and how it behaves. An <strong>object</strong> is a real instance created from that blueprint \u2014 it exists in memory, holds actual data, and can run the methods defined in the class.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 architectural drawing vs actual house</span>\n    <p>A class is an architectural drawing. An object is an actual house built from it. One drawing can produce many independent houses \u2014 each with its own address, its own paint colour, its own residents. Changing what happens in one house doesn't affect the others. And the drawing itself stays unchanged no matter how many houses you build from it.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Dog</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">pass</span>                    <span class=\"c\"># minimal valid class</span>\n\nbruno = Dog()               <span class=\"c\"># object 1 \u2014 independent instance</span>\ntommy = Dog()               <span class=\"c\"># object 2 \u2014 independent instance</span>\n\nprint(type(bruno))          <span class=\"c\"># &lt;class '__main__.Dog'&gt;</span>\nprint(bruno <span class=\"k\">is</span> tommy)      <span class=\"c\"># False \u2014 different objects in memory</span></div>\n\n  <h3 id=\"oop-init\">__init__ \u2014 the constructor</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 __init__</span>\n    <p>A special method that runs <strong>automatically</strong> the moment an object is created. Used to assign initial data to the object. You never call it yourself \u2014 Python calls it the instant you write <code>Dog(\"Bruno\", 3)</code>.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 hospital admission form</span>\n    <p>The moment a patient walks in, staff immediately fill an admission form \u2014 name, age, condition. You don't ask \"should we fill the form?\" \u2014 it happens automatically. That's <code>__init__</code>: the form that gets filled the instant an object is created.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Dog</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, name, age):\n        self.name = name     <span class=\"c\"># assign data to THIS object</span>\n        self.age  = age\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">bark</span>(self):\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"{self.name} says: Woof!\"</span>)\n\nbruno = Dog(<span class=\"g\">\"Bruno\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># __init__ runs automatically here</span>\ntommy = Dog(<span class=\"g\">\"Tommy\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">5</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># separate object \u2014 separate data</span>\n\nbruno.bark()               <span class=\"c\"># \"Bruno says: Woof!\"</span>\ntommy.bark()               <span class=\"c\"># \"Tommy says: Woof!\"  \u2014 same method, own data</span></div>\n\n  <h3>self \u2014 the object referring to itself</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 self</span>\n    <p>A parameter that represents the object itself inside a method. Allows each object to access and modify its own data rather than someone else's. Every method inside a class must have <code>self</code> as the first parameter \u2014 no exceptions. Python passes it automatically when you call a method.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 the word \"my\"</span>\n    <p>When you say \"my name is Aman\", the word \"my\" refers specifically to you \u2014 not anyone else in the room. <code>self</code> is Python's \"my\". When <code>bruno.bark()</code> runs, <code>self.name</code> means \"my name\" \u2014 Bruno's name, not Tommy's.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># When you call: bruno.bark()</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Python actually does: Dog.bark(bruno)</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># self IS the object \u2014 Python passes it silently</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Car</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, brand):\n        self.brand = brand   <span class=\"c\"># self = this specific Car object</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">honk</span>(self):\n        <span class=\"c\"># self.brand = \"this car's brand\"</span>\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"{self.brand} goes beep beep!\"</span>)\n\nlambo = Car(<span class=\"g\">\"Lambo\"</span>)\ntesla = Car(<span class=\"g\">\"Tesla\"</span>)\nlambo.honk()  <span class=\"c\"># \"Lambo goes beep beep!\"</span>\ntesla.honk()  <span class=\"c\"># \"Tesla goes beep beep!\"  \u2014 same method, self differs</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 2. ATTRIBUTES & METHODS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"oop-attrs\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>Attributes & Methods \u2014 data and behaviour</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">MLModel</span>:\n    <span class=\"c\"># Class attribute \u2014 shared across ALL instances</span>\n    framework = <span class=\"g\">\"PyTorch\"</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, name: str, lr: float = <span class=\"y\">0.001</span>):\n        <span class=\"c\"># Instance attributes \u2014 unique to each object</span>\n        self.name    = name\n        self.lr      = lr\n        self._weights = []          <span class=\"c\"># _single underscore = \"internal use\" convention</span>\n        self.__secret = <span class=\"g\">\"hidden\"</span>   <span class=\"c\"># __double underscore = name-mangled, truly private</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">train</span>(self, data):\n        <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Instance method \u2014 receives self.\"\"\"</span>\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Training {self.name}...\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"o\">@classmethod</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">from_config</span>(cls, config: dict) -> <span class=\"g\">\"MLModel\"</span>:\n        <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Class method \u2014 receives cls. Used as alternative constructor.\"\"\"</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> cls(config[<span class=\"g\">\"name\"</span>], config.get(<span class=\"g\">\"lr\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">0.001</span>))\n\n    <span class=\"o\">@staticmethod</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">validate_lr</span>(lr: float) -> bool:\n        <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Static method \u2014 no self or cls. Pure utility function.\"\"\"</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"y\">0</span> < lr < <span class=\"y\">1</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Usage</span>\nmodel1 = MLModel(<span class=\"g\">\"BERT\"</span>, lr=<span class=\"y\">2e-5</span>)\nmodel2 = MLModel.from_config({<span class=\"g\">\"name\"</span>: <span class=\"g\">\"GPT\"</span>})   <span class=\"c\"># alternative constructor</span>\nMLModel.validate_lr(<span class=\"y\">0.001</span>)                      <span class=\"c\"># no instance needed</span>\nprint(MLModel.framework)                         <span class=\"c\"># \"PyTorch\" \u2014 class attribute</span>\nprint(model1.framework)                          <span class=\"c\"># \"PyTorch\" \u2014 accessed via instance too</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 3. FOUR PILLARS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"oop-pillars\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>The Four Pillars</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Important framing</span>\n    <p>The four pillars are <strong>principles</strong>, not Python features. Rules that engineers figured out to keep large codebases manageable. Python does not enforce them. Ignoring them at scale breaks everything.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 160\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">The Four Pillars \u2014 what each one actually does</text>\n      <g text-anchor=\"middle\">\n        <rect x=\"15\" y=\"38\" width=\"155\" height=\"110\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">Encapsulation</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Hides DATA.</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Protects internal</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">state from direct</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"122\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">access.</text>\n        <text x=\"92\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">__ + getters/setters</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"185\" y=\"38\" width=\"155\" height=\"110\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Abstraction</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Hides COMPLEXITY.</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Shows only what</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">the caller needs</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"122\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">to see.</text>\n        <text x=\"262\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">ABC + @abstractmethod</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"355\" y=\"38\" width=\"155\" height=\"110\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#F4EFFE\" stroke=\"#D9C8FA\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">Inheritance</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Reuse parent code.</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Child gets parent</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">behaviour for</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"122\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">free. is-a.</text>\n        <text x=\"432\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">class Child(Parent)</text>\n\n        <rect x=\"525\" y=\"38\" width=\"160\" height=\"110\" rx=\"8\" fill=\"#FEF5E7\" stroke=\"#F4D49A\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"62\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#C2710C\">Polymorphism</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"80\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Same interface,</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"94\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">different behaviour.</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Runtime decides</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"122\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">which runs.</text>\n        <text x=\"605\" y=\"140\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#C2710C\">dynamic dispatch</text>\n      </g>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <h3>Pillar 1 \u2014 Inheritance</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Inheritance</span>\n    <p>A mechanism where a child class automatically acquires the properties and behaviours of a parent class, allowing code reuse and establishing an <strong>is-a</strong> relationship between classes.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 Dog and Cat are Animals</span>\n    <p>Dog and Cat both breathe, eat, and sleep. Write that logic once in <code>Animal</code>. Dog and Cat get it automatically \u2014 no copy-paste. If you change how breathing works, you change it in one place and both inherit the fix.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Staff</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, name, employee_id, salary):\n        self.name        = name\n        self.employee_id = employee_id\n        self.salary      = salary\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">get_details</span>(self):\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"ID: {self.employee_id} | Name: {self.name}\"</span>)\n\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Doctor</span>(Staff):                     <span class=\"c\"># Doctor IS-A Staff</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, name, employee_id, salary, specialization):\n        <span class=\"c\"># ALWAYS call super().__init__() first</span>\n        <span class=\"c\"># Without it, name/employee_id/salary are never set on self</span>\n        super().__init__(name, employee_id, salary)\n        self.specialization = specialization    <span class=\"c\"># Doctor-specific attribute</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">prescribe</span>(self, patient):\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Dr {self.name} prescribing for {patient}\"</span>)\n\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Nurse</span>(Staff):                      <span class=\"c\"># Nurse IS-A Staff</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, name, employee_id, salary, ward):\n        super().__init__(name, employee_id, salary)\n        self.ward = ward\n\ndoc   = Doctor(<span class=\"g\">\"Alice\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"D001\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">200000</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"Cardiology\"</span>)\nnurse = Nurse(<span class=\"g\">\"Bob\"</span>,   <span class=\"g\">\"N001\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">80000</span>,  <span class=\"g\">\"ICU\"</span>)\n\ndoc.get_details()    <span class=\"c\"># inherited from Staff \u2014 no need to rewrite</span>\nnurse.get_details()  <span class=\"c\"># same method, Staff provides it</span></div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">super() \u2014 why it's not optional</span>\n    <p>Without <code>super().__init__()</code>, the parent's <code>__init__</code> never runs. So <code>self.name</code>, <code>self.employee_id</code>, <code>self.salary</code> are never set. Any method that touches them crashes with <code>AttributeError</code>. This is the #1 inheritance bug beginners hit.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <h3>Pillar 2 \u2014 Polymorphism</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Polymorphism</span>\n    <p>The ability of different classes to be treated through the same interface, where each class implements that interface in its own way. The calling code doesn't know or care which class it's dealing with \u2014 it just calls the method and each class responds differently.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 \"Speak!\" produces different sounds</span>\n    <p>Tell a dog to speak \u2014 it barks. Tell a cat to speak \u2014 it meows. Tell a parrot to speak \u2014 it says your name. Same instruction (\"speak\"). Different behaviour depending on who received it. The person giving the instruction doesn't need to know what animal they're talking to.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Doctor</span>(Staff):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">get_details</span>(self):                 <span class=\"c\"># overrides Staff's version</span>\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Dr {self.name} | {self.specialization}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Nurse</span>(Staff):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">get_details</span>(self):                 <span class=\"c\"># overrides Staff's version</span>\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Nurse {self.name} | Ward {self.ward}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Polymorphism in action \u2014 same loop, different behaviour</span>\nstaff_list = [Doctor(...), Nurse(...), Doctor(...)]\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> member <span class=\"k\">in</span> staff_list:\n    member.get_details()   <span class=\"c\"># Python picks the right version at runtime</span>\n    <span class=\"c\"># This runtime decision = dynamic dispatch</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># No isinstance() checks needed \u2014 that's the whole point</span></div>\n\n  <h3>Pillar 3 \u2014 Encapsulation</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Encapsulation</span>\n    <p>Bundling data and methods within a single unit, while restricting direct access from outside to protect data integrity. It's not just hiding data \u2014 it's <strong>controlling how data is changed</strong>.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 ATM machine</span>\n    <p>You can deposit and withdraw at an ATM, but you cannot open the machine and grab cash directly. The bank controls every interaction with your money through defined interfaces (deposit, withdraw) that have rules (can't withdraw more than balance, can't deposit negative amounts). The balance itself is locked away.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">BankAccount</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, balance: float):\n        self.__balance = balance       <span class=\"c\"># __ makes it private (name-mangled)</span>\n                                       <span class=\"c\"># outsiders cannot access it directly</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">deposit</span>(self, amount: float):\n        <span class=\"k\">if</span> amount <= <span class=\"y\">0</span>:\n            print(<span class=\"g\">\"Amount must be positive.\"</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">else</span>:\n            self.__balance += amount\n            print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Deposited \u20b9{amount}. Balance: \u20b9{self.__balance}\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">withdraw</span>(self, amount: float):\n        <span class=\"k\">if</span> amount > self.__balance:\n            print(<span class=\"g\">\"Insufficient funds.\"</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">else</span>:\n            self.__balance -= amount\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">get_balance</span>(self) -> float:    <span class=\"c\"># getter \u2014 controlled READ access</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self.__balance\n\nacc = BankAccount(<span class=\"y\">10000</span>)\nacc.deposit(<span class=\"y\">5000</span>)\nprint(acc.get_balance())          <span class=\"c\"># 15000 \u2014 via getter</span>\nprint(acc.__balance)              <span class=\"c\"># AttributeError \u2014 private!</span>\nprint(acc._BankAccount__balance)  <span class=\"c\"># 15000 \u2014 name-mangling (exists but don't use)</span></div>\n\n  <h3>Pillar 4 \u2014 Abstraction</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Abstraction</span>\n    <p>Hiding internal implementation complexity and exposing only what is necessary to the user. The caller knows <em>what</em> to call, not <em>how</em> it works inside. Implemented in Python using Abstract Base Classes (ABC) and the <code>@abstractmethod</code> decorator.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 Google Maps</span>\n    <p>You type a destination and press \"Go\". Satellite calculations, real-time traffic data, route optimisation algorithms, server calls \u2014 all of it happens invisibly. You see one clean interface: a map and a start button. That's abstraction: hide the complex machinery, expose the simple surface.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> abc <span class=\"k\">import</span> ABC, abstractmethod\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Staff</span>(ABC):                       <span class=\"c\"># ABC = Abstract Base Class</span>\n    <span class=\"o\">@abstractmethod</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">get_details</span>(self):\n        <span class=\"k\">pass</span>                           <span class=\"c\"># no implementation here</span>\n                                       <span class=\"c\"># subclasses MUST implement this</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Python refuses to instantiate Staff directly:</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># s = Staff()  \u2192  TypeError: Can't instantiate abstract class Staff</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Doctor</span>(Staff):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">get_details</span>(self):             <span class=\"c\"># implemented \u2014 Python is satisfied</span>\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Dr {self.name}\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Nurse</span>(Staff):\n    <span class=\"k\">pass</span>                               <span class=\"c\"># forgot to implement get_details</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># n = Nurse()  \u2192  TypeError: Can't instantiate \u2014 get_details not implemented</span></div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Encapsulation vs Abstraction \u2014 the most common interview trap</span>\n    <p>These are different and interviewers specifically test whether you know the difference.</p>\n    <table class=\"tbl\">\n      <tr><th>Concept</th><th>What it hides</th><th>Why</th><th>How in Python</th></tr>\n      <tr><td><strong>Encapsulation</strong></td><td>DATA \u2014 the internal state</td><td>Protects integrity. Controls who can change it and how.</td><td><code>self.__attr</code> + getter/setter methods with validation</td></tr>\n      <tr><td><strong>Abstraction</strong></td><td>COMPLEXITY \u2014 the implementation</td><td>Simplifies the interface. Caller doesn't need to know how it works.</td><td><code>ABC</code> + <code>@abstractmethod</code></td></tr>\n    </table>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 4. MAGIC METHODS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"oop-magic\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Magic / Dunder Methods</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Magic Methods / Dunder Methods</span>\n    <p>Special methods with double underscores before and after their name (<code>__method__</code>). They let you define how your custom objects behave with built-in Python operations like <code>print()</code>, <code>len()</code>, <code>+</code>, <code>==</code>, <code>in</code>, and iteration. Python calls them automatically \u2014 you never call them directly.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th>You write</th><th>Python calls</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>Car(\"Lambo\", 2024)</code></td><td><code>__init__</code></td><td>Create and initialise object</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>print(car1)</code></td><td><code>__str__</code></td><td>User-friendly string representation</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>repr(car1)</code></td><td><code>__repr__</code></td><td>Developer/debugging string representation</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>len(garage)</code></td><td><code>__len__</code></td><td>Number of items</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>car1 + car2</code></td><td><code>__add__</code></td><td>Addition behaviour</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>car1 == car2</code></td><td><code>__eq__</code></td><td>Equality check</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>car1 &lt; car2</code></td><td><code>__lt__</code></td><td>Less-than comparison</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>x in garage</code></td><td><code>__contains__</code></td><td>Membership test</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>garage[0]</code></td><td><code>__getitem__</code></td><td>Index access</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>for car in garage</code></td><td><code>__iter__</code></td><td>Iteration support</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>bool(car)</code></td><td><code>__bool__</code></td><td>Truth value testing</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><code>garage()</code></td><td><code>__call__</code></td><td>Call instance like a function</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <h3>__str__ vs __repr__ \u2014 the distinction that matters</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The rule</span>\n    <p><code>__str__</code> is for <strong>end users</strong> \u2014 a readable, friendly description. Called by <code>print()</code> and <code>str()</code>.<br>\n    <code>__repr__</code> is for <strong>developers</strong> \u2014 should ideally be enough to recreate the object. Called by <code>repr()</code> and in the interactive shell.<br>\n    If Python can't find <code>__str__</code>, it falls back to <code>__repr__</code>. If you only define one, define <code>__repr__</code>.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Car</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, brand, year):\n        self.brand = brand\n        self.year  = year\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__str__</span>(self) -> str:\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> f<span class=\"g\">\"{self.brand} ({self.year})\"</span>   <span class=\"c\"># friendly, for users</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__repr__</span>(self) -> str:\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> f<span class=\"g\">\"Car(brand='{self.brand}', year={self.year})\"</span>  <span class=\"c\"># for devs</span>\n\ncar1 = Car(<span class=\"g\">\"Lambo\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">2024</span>)\nprint(str(car1))    <span class=\"c\"># \"Lambo (2024)\"                  \u2014 __str__</span>\nprint(repr(car1))   <span class=\"c\"># \"Car(brand='Lambo', year=2024)\"  \u2014 __repr__</span>\nprint(car1)         <span class=\"c\"># \"Lambo (2024)\"                  \u2014 print uses __str__</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># __eq__ \u2014 by default, == checks identity (is). Override to check values.</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Car</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__eq__</span>(self, other):\n        <span class=\"k\">if not</span> isinstance(other, Car): <span class=\"k\">return</span> NotImplemented\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self.brand == other.brand <span class=\"k\">and</span> self.year == other.year\n\ncar1 = Car(<span class=\"g\">\"Lambo\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">2024</span>)\ncar2 = Car(<span class=\"g\">\"Lambo\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">2024</span>)\nprint(car1 == car2)   <span class=\"c\"># True \u2014 same values</span>\nprint(car1 <span class=\"k\">is</span> car2)   <span class=\"c\"># False \u2014 different objects</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 5. OPERATOR OVERLOADING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"oop-overload\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Operator Overloading</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Operator Overloading</span>\n    <p>Redefining what built-in operators (<code>+</code>, <code>-</code>, <code>*</code>, <code>==</code>, <code>&lt;</code>) mean for custom objects by implementing the corresponding magic methods. The operators themselves don't change \u2014 their behaviour for your class does.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Magic methods = the tool. Operator overloading = one use of that tool.</span>\n    <p>They're the same thing looked at from different angles. <code>__add__</code> is a magic method. Using <code>__add__</code> to make <code>cart1 + cart2</code> merge two shopping carts is operator overloading.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Cart</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, items: list, total: float):\n        self.items = items\n        self.total = total\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__add__</span>(self, other: <span class=\"g\">\"Cart\"</span>) -> <span class=\"g\">\"Cart\"</span>:\n        <span class=\"c\"># What cart1 + cart2 means</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> Cart(\n            items=self.items + other.items,\n            total=self.total + other.total\n        )\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__len__</span>(self) -> int:\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> len(self.items)          <span class=\"c\"># len(cart)</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__contains__</span>(self, item: str) -> bool:\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> item <span class=\"k\">in</span> self.items       <span class=\"c\"># \"shoes\" in cart</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__str__</span>(self) -> str:\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> f<span class=\"g\">\"Items: {self.items} | Total: \u20b9{self.total}\"</span>\n\ncart1 = Cart([<span class=\"g\">\"shoes\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"shirt\"</span>], <span class=\"y\">2500</span>)\ncart2 = Cart([<span class=\"g\">\"watch\"</span>], <span class=\"y\">5000</span>)\n\nmerged = cart1 + cart2                    <span class=\"c\"># calls __add__</span>\nprint(merged)                             <span class=\"c\"># Items: ['shoes','shirt','watch'] | Total: \u20b97500</span>\nprint(len(cart1))                         <span class=\"c\"># 2 \u2014 calls __len__</span>\nprint(<span class=\"g\">\"shoes\"</span> <span class=\"k\">in</span> cart1)                 <span class=\"c\"># True \u2014 calls __contains__</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 6. COMPOSITION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"oop-comp\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Composition vs Inheritance</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Composition</span>\n    <p>A design pattern where a class is built by <strong>containing</strong> objects of other classes rather than inheriting from them. Models a <strong>has-a</strong> relationship rather than is-a.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">A Car is not an Engine. A Car HAS an Engine.</span>\n    <p>You don't inherit Engine inside Car \u2014 that would mean \"a Car is a type of Engine\", which is wrong. Instead you put an Engine object inside Car as an attribute. The Engine handles engine behaviour. The Car handles car behaviour. Each can be changed, replaced, or tested independently.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <table class=\"tbl\">\n    <tr><th>Relationship</th><th>Question to ask</th><th>Use</th></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>is-a</strong></td><td>Is a Doctor a Staff member?</td><td>Inheritance</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>has-a</strong></td><td>Does a Car have an Engine?</td><td>Composition</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>is-a</strong></td><td>Is a Nurse a Staff member?</td><td>Inheritance</td></tr>\n    <tr><td><strong>has-a</strong></td><td>Does a Hospital have Doctors?</td><td>Composition</td></tr>\n  </table>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Engine</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, horsepower: int):\n        self.horsepower = horsepower\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">start</span>(self):\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Engine with {self.horsepower}hp started.\"</span>)\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">stop</span>(self):\n        print(<span class=\"g\">\"Engine stopped.\"</span>)\n\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Car</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, brand: str, horsepower: int):\n        self.brand  = brand\n        self.engine = Engine(horsepower)    <span class=\"c\"># Car HAS an Engine</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">start</span>(self):\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"{self.brand} is starting...\"</span>)\n        self.engine.start()                 <span class=\"c\"># delegate to Engine</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">stop</span>(self):\n        self.engine.stop()\n\ncar = Car(<span class=\"g\">\"Lambo\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">700</span>)\ncar.start()\n<span class=\"c\"># Lambo is starting...</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Engine with 700hp started.</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Benefit: swap the engine without touching Car</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">ElectricEngine</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">start</span>(self): print(<span class=\"g\">\"Silent electric motor started.\"</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">stop</span>(self):  print(<span class=\"g\">\"Electric motor stopped.\"</span>)\n\ntesla = Car(<span class=\"g\">\"Tesla\"</span>, <span class=\"y\">450</span>)\ntesla.engine = ElectricEngine()  <span class=\"c\"># swap at runtime \u2014 Car class unchanged</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 7. @PROPERTY \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"oop-property\"><span class=\"num\">07</span>@property \u2014 Pythonic access control</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why @property exists</span>\n    <p>You want the outside world to read an attribute (<code>obj.temperature</code>), but not set it to invalid values (<code>obj.temperature = -500</code>). You could use getter/setter methods \u2014 but then it reads like Java: <code>obj.get_temperature()</code>, <code>obj.set_temperature(25)</code>. Python's <code>@property</code> lets you write clean attribute-style code while adding validation logic behind the scenes.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Temperature</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, celsius: float):\n        self._celsius = celsius             <span class=\"c\"># single underscore = \"please don't touch\"</span>\n\n    <span class=\"o\">@property</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">celsius</span>(self) -> float:            <span class=\"c\"># GETTER \u2014 called on obj.celsius</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self._celsius\n\n    <span class=\"o\">@celsius.setter</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">celsius</span>(self, value: float):       <span class=\"c\"># SETTER \u2014 called on obj.celsius = x</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">if</span> value < -<span class=\"y\">273.15</span>:\n            <span class=\"k\">raise</span> ValueError(<span class=\"g\">\"Below absolute zero!\"</span>)\n        self._celsius = value\n\n    <span class=\"o\">@property</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">fahrenheit</span>(self) -> float:         <span class=\"c\"># computed property \u2014 no setter</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self._celsius * <span class=\"y\">9</span>/<span class=\"y\">5</span> + <span class=\"y\">32</span>\n\nt = Temperature(<span class=\"y\">25</span>)\nprint(t.celsius)       <span class=\"c\"># 25   \u2014 reads like an attribute, is a method</span>\nprint(t.fahrenheit)    <span class=\"c\"># 77.0 \u2014 computed on the fly</span>\nt.celsius = <span class=\"y\">30</span>         <span class=\"c\"># calls the setter with validation</span>\nt.celsius = -<span class=\"y\">300</span>       <span class=\"c\"># ValueError: Below absolute zero!</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 8. MRO \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"oop-mro\"><span class=\"num\">08</span>MRO \u2014 Method Resolution Order</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 MRO</span>\n    <p>The order in which Python searches classes to find a method when multiple inheritance is involved. Python uses the <strong>C3 linearisation algorithm</strong> to compute a deterministic, consistent order. Check it with <code>ClassName.__mro__</code> or <code>help(ClassName)</code>.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The diamond problem \u2014 why MRO matters</span>\n    <p>Class D inherits from B and C. Both B and C inherit from A. D calls a method. Which version does Python use \u2014 B's, C's, or A's? Without a clear rule, this is ambiguous. MRO provides the rule: search in the order given, depth-first, never revisiting a class twice, A comes last.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Diamond inheritance</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">A</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">who</span>(self): print(<span class=\"g\">\"A\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">B</span>(A):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">who</span>(self): print(<span class=\"g\">\"B\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">C</span>(A):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">who</span>(self): print(<span class=\"g\">\"C\"</span>)\n\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">D</span>(B, C):              <span class=\"c\"># B listed first</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">pass</span>\n\nd = D()\nd.who()                     <span class=\"c\"># \"B\" \u2014 B is first in MRO</span>\n\nprint(D.__mro__)\n<span class=\"c\"># (&lt;class 'D'&gt;, &lt;class 'B'&gt;, &lt;class 'C'&gt;, &lt;class 'A'&gt;, &lt;class 'object'&gt;)\n# MRO: D \u2192 B \u2192 C \u2192 A \u2192 object</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># super() in MRO \u2014 chains through all classes in MRO order</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">B</span>(A):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">who</span>(self):\n        print(<span class=\"g\">\"B\"</span>)\n        super().who()        <span class=\"c\"># calls next in MRO (C.who), not A.who directly</span></div>\n\n  <h2 id=\"oop-qa\"><span class=\"num\">09</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\"><h3>Answer before revealing</h3><button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button></div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the difference between Encapsulation and Abstraction?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Encapsulation hides DATA \u2014 it bundles data and methods together and restricts direct access to protect data integrity. Implemented with private attributes (double underscore) and getter/setter methods with validation. Abstraction hides COMPLEXITY \u2014 it exposes only the interface the caller needs, hiding the implementation. Implemented with abstract base classes and @abstractmethod. Memory trick: Encapsulation = protect the data. Abstraction = simplify the interface.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Why must you call super().__init__() in a child class?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Without super().__init__(), the parent's __init__ never runs. That means all attributes set in the parent's __init__ \u2014 like self.name, self.salary \u2014 are never assigned to the object. Any method that accesses those attributes will crash with AttributeError. super() calls the parent's __init__ and passes self (the child object) so the parent sets up its part of the object first, then the child adds its own attributes.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is dynamic dispatch?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Dynamic dispatch is Python's runtime decision about which version of a method to call when a method name exists in multiple classes. When you call member.get_details() on a list of Staff objects, Python looks at the actual type of each object at runtime \u2014 if it's a Doctor, it calls Doctor.get_details(); if it's a Nurse, it calls Nurse.get_details(). The decision happens at runtime (dynamic), not at compile time (static). This is what makes polymorphism work.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Inheritance vs Composition \u2014 when do you use each?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Inheritance (is-a): use when the child class genuinely is a specialised version of the parent. Doctor is-a Staff. The child shares the parent's entire interface. Composition (has-a): use when a class needs functionality from another class but isn't a type of it. Car has-a Engine. In practice, prefer composition \u2014 it gives loose coupling (change Engine without touching Car), supports multiple instances of a component, and avoids the fragile base class problem. Use inheritance when you genuinely have an is-a relationship and you want to benefit from polymorphism.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is name mangling in Python?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">When you define an attribute with double underscore (self.__balance), Python renames it to _ClassName__balance \u2014 this is name mangling. It makes it harder to access from outside the class accidentally, but not impossible. The purpose is to avoid name collisions in inheritance: if a parent class has __balance and a child class also has __balance, they don't clash because they're stored as _Parent__balance and _Child__balance. It's not true security \u2014 anyone can still access _BankAccount__balance if they know the mangled name.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is MRO and what algorithm does Python use?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Method Resolution Order is the order Python uses to search classes when looking up a method in multiple inheritance. Python uses the C3 linearisation algorithm to compute a deterministic, consistent order: it ensures each class appears before its parents, and respects the order you listed base classes. For class D(B, C), the MRO is D \u2192 B \u2192 C \u2192 A \u2192 object. Check with ClassName.__mro__. super() follows the MRO order \u2014 it calls the next class in the MRO, not necessarily the direct parent.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "py_advanced": "<main>\n  <h1>Advanced Python</h1>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-iterators\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Iterators & Generators</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">yield, lazy eval, memory efficiency</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-decorators\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Decorators</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Closures, wrappers, parameterised, functools.wraps</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-context\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Context Managers</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">__enter__, __exit__, contextlib, resource safety</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n    <h2>Revision</h2>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>Iterator protocol</strong>: __iter__ returns self, __next__ returns next value or raises StopIteration.</li>\n      <li><strong>Generator</strong>: function with yield. Computes values lazily \u2014 one at a time. 1M-item list = 8MB. Generator = ~120 bytes.</li>\n      <li><strong>yield from</strong>: delegate to another generator. Same as looping and yielding each item.</li>\n      <li><strong>Decorator</strong> = function that takes a function and returns a modified function. @decorator is sugar for func = decorator(func).</li>\n      <li><strong>Always use @functools.wraps(func)</strong> inside decorators to preserve __name__, __doc__.</li>\n      <li><strong>Parameterised decorator</strong>: decorator factory returns a decorator. Three levels of nesting.</li>\n      <li><strong>Context manager</strong>: __enter__ = setup, __exit__ = teardown (always runs, even on exception).</li>\n      <li><strong>@contextmanager</strong>: use yield inside a try/finally \u2014 code before yield = __enter__, finally = __exit__.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n\n<h2 id=\"py-iterators\"><span class=\"num\">10</span>Iterators & Generators</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Iterator Protocol</span>\n    <p>Any object that implements two methods: <code>__iter__()</code> (returns the iterator itself) and <code>__next__()</code> (returns the next value or raises <code>StopIteration</code> when exhausted). Python's <code>for</code> loop is syntactic sugar over this protocol \u2014 it calls <code>iter(obj)</code> then repeatedly calls <code>next()</code> until <code>StopIteration</code>. A <strong>generator</strong> is a function that uses <code>yield</code> to implement this protocol automatically, computing each value on demand rather than all upfront.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Generators are single-use \u2014 the exhausted iterator trap</span>\n    <p>Once a generator is exhausted, it's gone. <code>gen = (x for x in range(5))</code> \u2014 iterate once: 0,1,2,3,4. Iterate again: nothing. No error. Just empty. This bites people who store a generator, consume it in one place, then try to use it again elsewhere. If you need to iterate multiple times, convert to a list once: <code>items = list(gen)</code>. Or recreate the generator each time. Never assume a generator still has values without checking.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why generators matter for ML</span>\n    <p>Loading a 100GB dataset into a list would crash your machine. A generator loads and processes one batch at a time, keeping only one batch in memory at any moment. PyTorch's DataLoader uses this pattern. Understanding generators = understanding how large-scale training actually works.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 140\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">List vs Generator \u2014 memory usage comparison</text>\n      <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"290\" height=\"90\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#FDEAEF\" stroke=\"#F6C0CF\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">List \u2014 all values in memory</text>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">[x**2 for x in range(1_000_000)]</text>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">~8 MB RAM immediately</text>\n      <text x=\"165\" y=\"115\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">All computed upfront</text>\n      <rect x=\"390\" y=\"38\" width=\"290\" height=\"90\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Generator \u2014 one value at a time</text>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">(x**2 for x in range(1_000_000))</text>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"100\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">~120 bytes RAM</text>\n      <text x=\"535\" y=\"115\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#5C6175\">Computed lazily on next()</text>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Iterator protocol \u2014 __iter__ and __next__</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">CountUp</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__init__</span>(self, limit): self.limit, self.current = limit, <span class=\"y\">0</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__iter__</span>(self): <span class=\"k\">return</span> self            <span class=\"c\"># returns itself</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__next__</span>(self):\n        <span class=\"k\">if</span> self.current >= self.limit:\n            <span class=\"k\">raise</span> StopIteration               <span class=\"c\"># signals end of iteration</span>\n        self.current += <span class=\"y\">1</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self.current\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> n <span class=\"k\">in</span> CountUp(<span class=\"y\">3</span>): print(n)  <span class=\"c\"># 1, 2, 3</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Generator function \u2014 simpler way using yield</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">count_up</span>(limit):\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">1</span>, limit + <span class=\"y\">1</span>):\n        <span class=\"k\">yield</span> i   <span class=\"c\"># pauses here, returns value, resumes on next()</span>\n\ngen = count_up(<span class=\"y\">3</span>)\nnext(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># 1</span>\nnext(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># 2</span>\nnext(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># 3</span>\nnext(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># StopIteration</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Real ML use case \u2014 batch generator</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">batch_generator</span>(data, batch_size=<span class=\"y\">32</span>):\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"Yields one batch at a time \u2014 never loads full dataset into memory.\"\"\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">0</span>, len(data), batch_size):\n        <span class=\"k\">yield</span> data[i:i + batch_size]\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> batch <span class=\"k\">in</span> batch_generator(huge_dataset):\n    model.train(batch)   <span class=\"c\"># only one batch in memory at a time</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Generator expression (lazy list comprehension)</span>\ngen = (x**<span class=\"y\">2</span> <span class=\"k\">for</span> x <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">1_000_000</span>))   <span class=\"c\"># () not []</span>\ntotal = sum(gen)   <span class=\"c\"># computed lazily, never all in memory\n\n# yield from \u2014 delegate to another generator</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">chain</span>(*iterables):\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> it <span class=\"k\">in</span> iterables:\n        <span class=\"k\">yield from</span> it   <span class=\"c\"># same as: for x in it: yield x</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 11. DECORATORS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-decorators\"><span class=\"num\">11</span>Decorators</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Decorator</span>\n    <p>A function that takes another function as input and returns a modified version of it. <code>@decorator</code> above a function definition is syntactic sugar for <code>func = decorator(func)</code>. The decorator wraps the original function in a new function \u2014 adding behaviour before, after, or around the original call without modifying the original function's code. This is how Flask registers routes, Django checks login, and pytest marks tests.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 a security guard at a door</span>\n    <p>The original function is a room. The decorator is a security guard at the door. Every time someone tries to enter the room (call the function), the guard intercepts them first \u2014 checks credentials, logs the visit, starts a timer. If they pass, the guard lets them in and the room does its thing. When they leave, the guard stops the timer and logs the duration. The room itself hasn't changed at all \u2014 the guard is entirely outside it.<br><br>\n    <code>@functools.wraps(func)</code> is critical \u2014 without it, the decorator overwrites the original function's name and docstring. Your debugger and logs start showing \"wrapper\" everywhere instead of the actual function name.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">What a decorator is \u2014 before any code</span>\n    <p>A decorator is a function that takes another function as input and returns a modified version of it. <code>@timer</code> above a function definition is just shorthand for <code>my_function = timer(my_function)</code>. That's it. The @ syntax is pure syntactic sugar.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Step 1: understand closures first</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">multiplier</span>(factor):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">multiply</span>(x):\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> x * factor    <span class=\"c\"># inner function \"captures\" outer variable</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> multiply\n\ndouble = multiplier(<span class=\"y\">2</span>)\ndouble(<span class=\"y\">5</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># \u2192 10   (factor=2 is remembered)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Step 2: basic decorator</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> time\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> functools <span class=\"k\">import</span> wraps\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">timer</span>(func):\n    <span class=\"o\">@wraps</span>(func)   <span class=\"c\"># preserves func's __name__, __doc__ etc.</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">wrapper</span>(*args, **kwargs):\n        start = time.time()\n        result = func(*args, **kwargs)     <span class=\"c\"># call original function</span>\n        end = time.time()\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"{func.__name__} took {end-start:.4f}s\"</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> result\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> wrapper\n\n<span class=\"o\">@timer</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">train_model</span>(data):      <span class=\"c\"># same as: train_model = timer(train_model)</span>\n    time.sleep(<span class=\"y\">1</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"g\">\"done\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Step 3: parameterized decorator (decorator factory)</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">retry</span>(max_attempts=<span class=\"y\">3</span>, exceptions=(Exception,)):\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">decorator</span>(func):\n        <span class=\"o\">@wraps</span>(func)\n        <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">wrapper</span>(*args, **kwargs):\n            <span class=\"k\">for</span> attempt <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(max_attempts):\n                <span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n                    <span class=\"k\">return</span> func(*args, **kwargs)\n                <span class=\"k\">except</span> exceptions <span class=\"k\">as</span> e:\n                    <span class=\"k\">if</span> attempt == max_attempts - <span class=\"y\">1</span>: <span class=\"k\">raise</span>\n                    print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Retry {attempt+1}/{max_attempts}: {e}\"</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> wrapper\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> decorator\n\n<span class=\"o\">@retry</span>(max_attempts=<span class=\"y\">5</span>, exceptions=(ConnectionError,))\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">call_api</span>(url):\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> requests.get(url)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Multiple decorators \u2014 applied bottom to top</span>\n<span class=\"o\">@timer</span>\n<span class=\"o\">@retry</span>(max_attempts=<span class=\"y\">3</span>)\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">fetch_data</span>(url): ...\n<span class=\"c\"># equivalent to: fetch_data = timer(retry(max_attempts=3)(fetch_data))</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 12. CONTEXT MANAGERS \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-context\"><span class=\"num\">12</span>Context Managers</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Context Manager</span>\n    <p>An object that defines what happens when entering and exiting a <code>with</code> block. Implements two methods: <code>__enter__()</code> runs at the start of the block (setup \u2014 open file, acquire lock, start transaction) and <code>__exit__()</code> runs at the end (teardown \u2014 close file, release lock, commit/rollback). <code>__exit__</code> is guaranteed to run even if an exception occurs inside the block. This guarantee is the entire point.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 a surgical suite with mandatory cleanup protocol</span>\n    <p>Before surgery: sterilise the room, prepare instruments, set monitors (enter). After surgery \u2014 success or complication \u2014 the protocol always runs: clean instruments, log the procedure, reset the room (exit). There is no path out of a surgery that skips the cleanup. <code>with</code> blocks work identically: there is no path out of the block that skips <code>__exit__</code>.<br><br>\n    Without context managers: you must remember to close every file, release every lock, and commit every transaction manually. One exception anywhere loses a file handle or holds a lock forever. <code>with open()</code> made this a solved problem.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Exception suppression \u2014 __exit__ can swallow errors silently</span>\n    <p><code>__exit__</code> receives the exception type, value, and traceback. If it returns <code>True</code>, the exception is suppressed \u2014 execution continues after the <code>with</code> block as if nothing happened. This is occasionally useful but usually catastrophic if done accidentally. If your <code>__exit__</code> forgets to return <code>False</code> (or returns <code>None</code>, which is falsy), exceptions propagate correctly. If it returns <code>True</code>, you have just hidden every error that occurs in that block.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The problem they solve</span>\n    <p><code>with open(\"file.txt\") as f:</code> \u2014 you've used this countless times. But why? Because even if an exception occurs inside the <code>with</code> block, the file is guaranteed to close. Without context managers, a crash mid-read would leave the file handle open \u2014 a resource leak. Context managers guarantee cleanup regardless of how the block exits.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># How context managers work internally</span>\n<span class=\"k\">class</span> <span class=\"o\">Timer</span>:\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__enter__</span>(self):\n        self.start = time.time()\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> self          <span class=\"c\"># value assigned to \"as\" variable</span>\n\n    <span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">__exit__</span>(self, exc_type, exc_val, exc_tb):\n        <span class=\"c\"># exc_type/val/tb are None if no exception occurred</span>\n        elapsed = time.time() - self.start\n        print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Elapsed: {elapsed:.3f}s\"</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">return</span> <span class=\"k\">False</span>  <span class=\"c\"># False = don't suppress exceptions</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> Timer() <span class=\"k\">as</span> t:\n    time.sleep(<span class=\"y\">0.5</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># always prints elapsed, even if exception</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># contextlib \u2014 simpler way with generators</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> contextlib <span class=\"k\">import</span> contextmanager\n\n<span class=\"o\">@contextmanager</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">managed_db_connection</span>(url):\n    conn = connect(url)\n    <span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n        <span class=\"k\">yield</span> conn           <span class=\"c\"># everything before yield = __enter__</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">finally</span>:\n        conn.close()         <span class=\"c\"># everything in finally = __exit__</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> managed_db_connection(<span class=\"g\">\"postgres://...\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> conn:\n    conn.execute(<span class=\"g\">\"SELECT 1\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># conn.close() always called after</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Multiple context managers in one line</span>\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> open(<span class=\"g\">\"in.txt\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> infile, open(<span class=\"g\">\"out.txt\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"w\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> outfile:\n    outfile.write(infile.read())</div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 13. THREADING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  \n\n</main>",
  "py_concurrency": "<main>\n  <h1>Concurrency & Async</h1>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"con-model\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Concurrency Models</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Which to use when \u2014 the decision</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"con-gil\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">The GIL</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Why it exists and what it prevents</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"con-threads\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Multithreading</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Locks, race conditions, deadlocks, ThreadPoolExecutor</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"con-multiproc\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Multiprocessing</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">ProcessPoolExecutor, queues, shared memory</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"con-async\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">05</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Asyncio</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Event loop, coroutines, async/await, gather</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n    <h2>Revision</h2>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>Three tools, three problems:</strong> Threading for I/O-bound (API calls), Multiprocessing for CPU-bound (computation), Asyncio for high-concurrency I/O (many simultaneous waits).</li>\n      <li><strong>GIL:</strong> Only one thread runs Python bytecode at a time. Threads share memory but don't achieve true CPU parallelism. Released during I/O waits and C extensions.</li>\n      <li><strong>Race condition:</strong> Two threads read-then-write the same variable. The second write overwrites the first, losing data. Fix: Lock.</li>\n      <li><strong>Deadlock:</strong> Thread A holds Lock 1, waits for Lock 2. Thread B holds Lock 2, waits for Lock 1. Both wait forever. Fix: always acquire locks in the same order.</li>\n      <li><strong>ThreadPoolExecutor:</strong> The clean way to run I/O-bound tasks in parallel. Use <code>executor.map(fn, items)</code>.</li>\n      <li><strong>ProcessPoolExecutor:</strong> Each process has its own Python interpreter and GIL. True parallelism for CPU-bound tasks. Inter-process communication via Queue or shared memory.</li>\n      <li><strong>Coroutine:</strong> A function that can pause and resume. Defined with <code>async def</code>. Pauses at <code>await</code> points, allowing other coroutines to run.</li>\n      <li><strong>Event loop:</strong> The scheduler that runs coroutines. Switches between them when they're waiting. Single-threaded \u2014 no thread safety issues.</li>\n      <li><strong>asyncio.gather():</strong> Run multiple coroutines concurrently and wait for all to complete. Returns list of results.</li>\n      <li><strong>Semaphore:</strong> Rate-limit concurrency. <code>asyncio.Semaphore(10)</code> means max 10 concurrent operations.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 1. DECISION \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"con-model\"><span class=\"num\">01</span>Which model to use \u2014 the decision</h2>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 200\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">Three concurrency models \u2014 match the tool to the bottleneck</text>\n      <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"200\" height=\"148\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#EEF0FF\" stroke=\"#C9CDFB\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"120\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">Threading</text>\n      <text x=\"120\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">I/O-bound tasks</text>\n      <text x=\"120\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">API calls, file reads</text>\n      <text x=\"120\" y=\"114\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">DB queries</text>\n      <text x=\"120\" y=\"134\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">GIL released on I/O</text>\n      <text x=\"120\" y=\"150\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Threads run in parallel</text>\n      <text x=\"120\" y=\"170\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#4F46E5\">ThreadPoolExecutor</text>\n\n      <rect x=\"250\" y=\"38\" width=\"200\" height=\"148\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Multiprocessing</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">CPU-bound tasks</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">Heavy computation</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"114\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">ML training, encoding</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"134\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Each process = own GIL</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"150\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">True CPU parallelism</text>\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"170\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#0E9384\">ProcessPoolExecutor</text>\n\n      <rect x=\"480\" y=\"38\" width=\"200\" height=\"148\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#F4EFFE\" stroke=\"#D9C8FA\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">Asyncio</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"82\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#5C6175\">High-concurrency I/O</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"98\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">10,000+ simultaneous</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"114\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#2b2f45\">connections/requests</span></text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"134\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Single thread, no locks</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"150\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9.5\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Cooperative multitasking</text>\n      <text x=\"580\" y=\"170\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#7C3AED\">async/await + gather</text>\n    </svg>\n    <figcaption>The bottleneck determines the tool. Waiting on I/O \u2192 threading or asyncio. Burning CPU \u2192 multiprocessing. High connection count with I/O waits \u2192 asyncio.</figcaption>\n  </figure>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 2. GIL \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"con-gil\"><span class=\"num\">02</span>The GIL \u2014 why Python threads don't speed up CPU work</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Global Interpreter Lock (GIL)</span>\n    <p>A mutex inside CPython that ensures only one thread executes Python bytecode at any given moment. It protects Python's internal memory management (reference counting) from corruption when multiple threads run simultaneously.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The concert venue analogy</span>\n    <p>Imagine a concert venue with one microphone. Only the person holding the microphone can perform (execute Python). Other performers (threads) must wait. When a performer needs to go backstage to do something else \u2014 like wait for a drink to be delivered (I/O) \u2014 they hand the microphone back and another performer can use it. This is exactly the GIL: released during I/O waits, held during CPU computation.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 160\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">GIL: CPU-bound threads don't run in parallel</text>\n      <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"110\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#FDEAEF\" stroke=\"#F6C0CF\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">2 CPU-bound threads (GIL hurts)</text>\n      <rect x=\"35\" y=\"76\" width=\"120\" height=\"18\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#D92D5C\"/>\n      <text x=\"95\" y=\"89\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"white\">Thread 1 runs</text>\n      <rect x=\"35\" y=\"100\" width=\"120\" height=\"18\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#E7E8F0\"/>\n      <text x=\"95\" y=\"113\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#999\">Thread 2 waits</text>\n      <rect x=\"165\" y=\"76\" width=\"120\" height=\"18\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#E7E8F0\"/>\n      <text x=\"225\" y=\"89\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"#999\">Thread 1 waits</text>\n      <rect x=\"165\" y=\"100\" width=\"120\" height=\"18\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#D92D5C\"/>\n      <text x=\"225\" y=\"113\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8.5\" fill=\"white\">Thread 2 runs</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">Takes same time as 1 thread \u2014 no speedup!</text>\n\n      <rect x=\"380\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"110\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">2 I/O-bound threads (GIL helps)</text>\n      <rect x=\"395\" y=\"76\" width=\"60\" height=\"18\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#0E9384\"/>\n      <text x=\"425\" y=\"89\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"white\">T1 compute</text>\n      <rect x=\"455\" y=\"76\" width=\"100\" height=\"18\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\"/>\n      <text x=\"505\" y=\"89\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"#0E9384\">T1 waiting for API</text>\n      <rect x=\"395\" y=\"100\" width=\"55\" height=\"18\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\"/>\n      <text x=\"422\" y=\"113\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"#0E9384\">T2 waits</text>\n      <rect x=\"450\" y=\"100\" width=\"110\" height=\"18\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#0E9384\"/>\n      <text x=\"505\" y=\"113\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"7\" fill=\"white\">T2 runs while T1 waits!</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"138\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Both threads make progress \u2014 real speedup!</text>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 3. THREADING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"con-threads\"><span class=\"num\">03</span>Multithreading \u2014 I/O-bound concurrency</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> threading\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> concurrent.futures <span class=\"k\">import</span> ThreadPoolExecutor\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> requests\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Basic thread \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">fetch_url</span>(url):\n    response = requests.get(url, timeout=<span class=\"y\">5</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> response.json()\n\nthread = threading.Thread(target=fetch_url, args=(<span class=\"g\">\"http://api.example.com\"</span>,))\nthread.start()\nthread.join()  <span class=\"c\"># block until thread completes</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 ThreadPoolExecutor \u2014 the production pattern (use this) \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\nurls = [<span class=\"g\">\"http://api1.com\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"http://api2.com\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"http://api3.com\"</span>]\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> ThreadPoolExecutor(max_workers=<span class=\"y\">10</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> executor:\n    <span class=\"c\"># map: same function, different inputs, runs concurrently</span>\n    results = list(executor.map(fetch_url, urls))   <span class=\"c\"># blocks until all done</span>\n\n    <span class=\"c\"># submit: more control \u2014 get Future objects back</span>\n    futures = {executor.submit(fetch_url, url): url <span class=\"k\">for</span> url <span class=\"k\">in</span> urls}\n    <span class=\"k\">from</span> concurrent.futures <span class=\"k\">import</span> as_completed\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> future <span class=\"k\">in</span> as_completed(futures):\n        url = futures[future]\n        <span class=\"k\">try</span>:\n            data = future.result()\n        <span class=\"k\">except</span> Exception <span class=\"k\">as</span> e:\n            print(f<span class=\"g\">\"Error for {url}: {e}\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <h3>Race conditions and Locks</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Race condition</span>\n    <p>When two threads read a shared variable, compute based on it, and write back \u2014 and the order of these operations is not guaranteed. The second thread's write overwrites the first thread's write, losing data. The bug is non-deterministic: it only appears when the threads interleave in exactly the wrong order, making it hard to reproduce and debug.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Race condition (WITHOUT lock) \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\ncounter = <span class=\"y\">0</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">increment_unsafe</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">global</span> counter\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> _ <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">100_000</span>):\n        <span class=\"c\"># This is NOT atomic \u2014 it's three operations:</span>\n        <span class=\"c\"># 1. READ counter</span>\n        <span class=\"c\"># 2. ADD 1</span>\n        <span class=\"c\"># 3. WRITE counter</span>\n        <span class=\"c\"># Another thread can interrupt between any two steps!</span>\n        counter += <span class=\"y\">1</span>\n\nthreads = [threading.Thread(target=increment_unsafe) <span class=\"k\">for</span> _ <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">5</span>)]\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> t <span class=\"k\">in</span> threads: t.start()\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> t <span class=\"k\">in</span> threads: t.join()\nprint(counter)  <span class=\"c\"># Should be 500,000 but might be 487,293 or any lower number</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Lock \u2014 mutual exclusion \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\nlock = threading.Lock()\ncounter = <span class=\"y\">0</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">increment_safe</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">global</span> counter\n    <span class=\"k\">for</span> _ <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">100_000</span>):\n        <span class=\"k\">with</span> lock:        <span class=\"c\"># only one thread in here at a time</span>\n            counter += <span class=\"y\">1</span>  <span class=\"c\"># all three operations are now protected</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Other synchronisation primitives \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\nrlock = threading.RLock()        <span class=\"c\"># reentrant lock \u2014 same thread can acquire multiple times</span>\nevent = threading.Event()        <span class=\"c\"># signal between threads: event.set(), event.wait()</span>\nsem   = threading.Semaphore(<span class=\"y\">5</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># max 5 threads in a section simultaneously</span>\ncond  = threading.Condition()    <span class=\"c\"># complex producer-consumer signalling</span></div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Deadlock \u2014 the most painful threading bug</span>\n    <p>Thread A acquires Lock 1, then waits for Lock 2. Thread B acquires Lock 2, then waits for Lock 1. Both wait forever. The program hangs silently with no error.<br><br>\n    <strong>Prevention rule:</strong> always acquire multiple locks in the same order across all threads. If every thread acquires Lock 1 before Lock 2, no deadlock can occur.</p>\n    <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># DEADLOCK</span>\nlock1 = threading.Lock()\nlock2 = threading.Lock()\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">thread_a</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> lock1:          <span class=\"c\"># acquires lock1</span>\n        time.sleep(<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">with</span> lock2:      <span class=\"c\"># waits for lock2 \u2014 but thread_b has it!</span>\n            ...\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">thread_b</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> lock2:          <span class=\"c\"># acquires lock2</span>\n        time.sleep(<span class=\"y\">0.1</span>)\n        <span class=\"k\">with</span> lock1:      <span class=\"c\"># waits for lock1 \u2014 but thread_a has it!</span>\n            ...            <span class=\"c\"># Both wait forever.</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># FIX \u2014 always acquire in the same order</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">thread_b_fixed</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> lock1:          <span class=\"c\"># same order as thread_a</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">with</span> lock2:\n            ...</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 4. MULTIPROCESSING \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"con-multiproc\"><span class=\"num\">04</span>Multiprocessing \u2014 true CPU parallelism</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why multiprocessing bypasses the GIL</span>\n    <p>Each Python process has its own interpreter, its own GIL, and its own memory space. When you spawn 4 worker processes, all 4 can execute Python bytecode simultaneously on 4 CPU cores \u2014 the GIL in process 1 doesn't affect process 2. The tradeoff: processes are heavier than threads (more memory, slower to start), and sharing data between processes requires explicit mechanisms (queues, shared memory, pipes).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">from</span> concurrent.futures <span class=\"k\">import</span> ProcessPoolExecutor\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> multiprocessing <span class=\"k\">as</span> mp\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 ProcessPoolExecutor \u2014 the clean, high-level API \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">heavy_compute</span>(n):\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"CPU-intensive: runs in a separate process, bypasses GIL.\"\"\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> sum(i ** <span class=\"y\">2</span> <span class=\"k\">for</span> i <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(n))\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> ProcessPoolExecutor(max_workers=mp.cpu_count()) <span class=\"k\">as</span> executor:\n    inputs = [<span class=\"y\">1_000_000</span>, <span class=\"y\">2_000_000</span>, <span class=\"y\">3_000_000</span>]\n    results = list(executor.map(heavy_compute, inputs))\n    <span class=\"c\"># Runs all 3 on separate CPU cores simultaneously</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Lower-level: Queue for inter-process communication \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">worker</span>(task_queue, result_queue):\n    <span class=\"k\">while True</span>:\n        item = task_queue.get()\n        <span class=\"k\">if</span> item <span class=\"k\">is None</span>:  <span class=\"c\"># poison pill \u2014 signal to stop</span>\n            <span class=\"k\">break</span>\n        result_queue.put(heavy_compute(item))\n\ntask_q   = mp.Queue()\nresult_q = mp.Queue()\nworkers  = [mp.Process(target=worker, args=(task_q, result_q)) <span class=\"k\">for</span> _ <span class=\"k\">in</span> range(<span class=\"y\">4</span>)]\n\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> w <span class=\"k\">in</span> workers: w.start()\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> item <span class=\"k\">in</span> [<span class=\"y\">1_000_000</span>, <span class=\"y\">2_000_000</span>]: task_q.put(item)\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> _ <span class=\"k\">in</span> workers: task_q.put(<span class=\"k\">None</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># send poison pills to stop workers</span>\n<span class=\"k\">for</span> w <span class=\"k\">in</span> workers: w.join()\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Shared memory \u2014 zero-copy array sharing (Python 3.8+) \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> multiprocessing <span class=\"k\">import</span> shared_memory\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> numpy <span class=\"k\">as</span> np\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Create 1M float64 numbers in shared memory \u2014 no copying between processes!</span>\nshm = shared_memory.SharedMemory(create=<span class=\"k\">True</span>, size=<span class=\"y\">1_000_000</span> * <span class=\"y\">8</span>)\narr = np.ndarray((<span class=\"y\">1_000_000</span>,), dtype=np.float64, buffer=shm.buf)\narr[:] = np.random.randn(<span class=\"y\">1_000_000</span>)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Worker processes attach to the same shared memory by name</span>\nshm.close()\nshm.unlink()  <span class=\"c\"># clean up when done</span></div>\n\n  <!-- \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 5. ASYNCIO \u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550\u2550 -->\n  <h2 id=\"con-async\"><span class=\"num\">05</span>Asyncio \u2014 cooperative multitasking</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The key mental model \u2014 it is NOT parallel</span>\n    <p>Asyncio is single-threaded. It does not run code simultaneously. Instead, it switches between tasks whenever a task is waiting (for network, disk, sleep). While Task A is waiting for an HTTP response, Task B runs. When the response arrives, the event loop switches back to Task A.<br><br>\n    Think of a chef cooking multiple dishes. They don't cook them all simultaneously \u2014 they're one person. But while pasta boils (waiting), they chop vegetables (another task). Asyncio is the chef's ability to fill waiting time with useful work.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <figure>\n    <svg viewBox=\"0 0 700 150\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" font-family=\"Inter, sans-serif\">\n      <text x=\"350\" y=\"20\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"13\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#191B27\">Async: fill waiting time with other work (single thread)</text>\n      <rect x=\"20\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"100\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#FDEAEF\" stroke=\"#F6C0CF\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">Synchronous \u2014 blocking</text>\n      <rect x=\"35\" y=\"74\" width=\"60\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#D92D5C\"/>\n      <text x=\"65\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">API call</text>\n      <rect x=\"95\" y=\"74\" width=\"100\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#E7E8F0\"/>\n      <text x=\"145\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"#999\">...waiting...</text>\n      <rect x=\"195\" y=\"74\" width=\"50\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#D92D5C\"/>\n      <text x=\"220\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">result</text>\n      <text x=\"170\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#D92D5C\">Thread blocked the entire wait</text>\n\n      <rect x=\"380\" y=\"38\" width=\"300\" height=\"100\" rx=\"10\" fill=\"#E5F6F3\" stroke=\"#A7E0D7\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"62\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"11\" font-weight=\"700\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Async \u2014 cooperative</text>\n      <rect x=\"395\" y=\"74\" width=\"55\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#0E9384\"/>\n      <text x=\"422\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">API call</text>\n      <rect x=\"450\" y=\"74\" width=\"90\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#4F46E5\"/>\n      <text x=\"495\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">other task runs!</text>\n      <rect x=\"540\" y=\"74\" width=\"50\" height=\"20\" rx=\"4\" fill=\"#0E9384\"/>\n      <text x=\"565\" y=\"88\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"8\" fill=\"white\">result</text>\n      <text x=\"530\" y=\"120\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"9\" fill=\"#0E9384\">Useful work done while waiting</text>\n    </svg>\n  </figure>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"k\">import</span> asyncio\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> aiohttp\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Coroutine \u2014 defined with async def \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\n<span class=\"k\">async def</span> <span class=\"o\">fetch</span>(session, url):\n    <span class=\"g\">\"\"\"async def makes this a coroutine. await pauses it, yields control.\"\"\"</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">async with</span> session.get(url) <span class=\"k\">as</span> resp:\n        <span class=\"k\">return await</span> resp.json()  <span class=\"c\"># pause here, let other coroutines run</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">async def</span> <span class=\"o\">main</span>():\n    urls = [<span class=\"g\">\"http://api1.com\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"http://api2.com\"</span>, <span class=\"g\">\"http://api3.com\"</span>]\n\n    <span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 asyncio.gather \u2014 run all concurrently, wait for all \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\n    <span class=\"k\">async with</span> aiohttp.ClientSession() <span class=\"k\">as</span> session:\n        tasks = [fetch(session, url) <span class=\"k\">for</span> url <span class=\"k\">in</span> urls]\n        results = <span class=\"k\">await</span> asyncio.gather(*tasks)  <span class=\"c\"># all 3 run concurrently!</span>\n        <span class=\"c\"># Returns list of results in same order as tasks</span>\n\n    <span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 gather with error handling \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\n    results = <span class=\"k\">await</span> asyncio.gather(*tasks, return_exceptions=<span class=\"k\">True</span>)\n    <span class=\"c\"># Exceptions are returned as values instead of propagating</span>\n\n    <span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 asyncio.wait \u2014 finer control \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\n    done, pending = <span class=\"k\">await</span> asyncio.wait(tasks,\n                                       timeout=<span class=\"y\">5.0</span>,\n                                       return_when=asyncio.FIRST_COMPLETED)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Run the event loop \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\nasyncio.run(main())   <span class=\"c\"># Python 3.7+ \u2014 creates event loop, runs coroutine, closes loop</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Semaphore \u2014 rate-limit concurrency \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\nsem = asyncio.Semaphore(<span class=\"y\">10</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># max 10 concurrent API calls</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">async def</span> <span class=\"o\">fetch_limited</span>(session, url):\n    <span class=\"k\">async with</span> sem:              <span class=\"c\"># only 10 coroutines here at once</span>\n        <span class=\"k\">return await</span> fetch(session, url)\n\n<span class=\"c\"># \u2500\u2500 Async generator \u2014 stream large data lazily \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500</span>\n<span class=\"k\">async def</span> <span class=\"o\">stream_rows</span>(db):\n    <span class=\"k\">async for</span> row <span class=\"k\">in</span> db.execute(<span class=\"g\">\"SELECT * FROM huge_table\"</span>):\n        <span class=\"k\">yield</span> row   <span class=\"c\"># process one row without loading all into memory</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">async for</span> row <span class=\"k\">in</span> stream_rows(db):\n    process(row)</div>\n\n  <h2 id=\"con-qa\"><span class=\"num\">06</span>Interview Q&amp;A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\"><h3>Answer before revealing</h3><button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button></div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the GIL and when does it matter?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">The Global Interpreter Lock is a mutex inside CPython that prevents multiple threads from executing Python bytecode simultaneously \u2014 only one thread holds the GIL at a time. For CPU-bound tasks (computation), threads cannot achieve true parallelism because they compete for the GIL. For I/O-bound tasks, the GIL is released while waiting for I/O (network, disk), so threads do provide real concurrency. The solution for CPU-bound parallelism is multiprocessing \u2014 each process has its own Python interpreter and its own GIL.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is a race condition and how do you prevent it?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">A race condition occurs when two or more threads access shared mutable state and the result depends on the order of execution. Classic example: two threads both read counter=5, both compute 5+1=6, both write 6. The expected result was 7, but we get 6 \u2014 one increment is lost. Prevention: use a Lock to ensure only one thread can be in the critical section (read-modify-write) at a time. Use <code>with lock:</code> as a context manager to ensure the lock is always released, even if an exception occurs.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Threading vs multiprocessing vs asyncio \u2014 when do you use each?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Threading: I/O-bound tasks where threads spend most of their time waiting (API calls, file reads, DB queries). The GIL is released during I/O so real concurrency is achieved. Multiprocessing: CPU-bound tasks that need true parallelism (data processing, ML inference, compression). Each process has its own GIL. Higher overhead than threads but achieves real CPU parallelism. Asyncio: high-concurrency I/O where you need thousands of simultaneous connections. Single-threaded cooperative multitasking \u2014 minimal overhead, no lock complexity, but requires your entire call stack to be async-aware.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is a coroutine and how does await work?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">A coroutine is a function defined with <code>async def</code> that can pause its execution and yield control back to the event loop. When execution reaches an <code>await</code> expression, the coroutine pauses at that point, the event loop scheduler runs other coroutines that are ready, and when the awaited operation completes, the coroutine resumes from where it paused. Critically, the pausing is cooperative \u2014 a coroutine must explicitly <code>await</code> to yield control. If a coroutine does CPU-heavy work without awaiting, it blocks the entire event loop.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is a deadlock and how do you prevent it?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">A deadlock occurs when two or more threads are each waiting for a resource held by the other, creating a circular dependency where no thread can proceed. Classic example: Thread A holds Lock 1 and waits for Lock 2. Thread B holds Lock 2 and waits for Lock 1. Prevention strategies: (1) Lock ordering \u2014 always acquire multiple locks in the same order across all threads. (2) Lock timeout \u2014 use <code>lock.acquire(timeout=5)</code> and handle failure. (3) Use higher-level abstractions like queues instead of raw locks. (4) Avoid holding locks during blocking operations.</div></details>\n</main>\n",
  "py_testing": "<main>\n  <h1>Testing & Debugging</h1>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-wrap\">\n    <h2 class=\"roadmap-title\">What we'll cover</h2>\n    <div class=\"roadmap-grid\">\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-testing\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">01</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">pytest Basics</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Test functions, assertions, fixtures, parametrize</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-testing\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">02</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Mocking</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">unittest.mock, patch, MagicMock \u2014 isolate dependencies</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-testing\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">03</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Profiling</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">cProfile, pstats, timeit \u2014 find the bottleneck</span></div></div>\n      <div class=\"rm-item rm-done\" data-target=\"py-testing\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><span class=\"rm-num\">04</span><div class=\"rm-text\"><span class=\"rm-label\">Logging</span><span class=\"rm-sub\">Levels, formatters, handlers \u2014 structured observability</span></div></div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"panel\">\n    <h2>Revision</h2>\n    <ol>\n      <li><strong>pytest's discovery and assert rewriting:</strong> any function named <code>test_*</code> in a file named <code>test_*.py</code> is auto-discovered \u2014 no boilerplate class needed. pytest rewrites plain <code>assert</code> statements to show a detailed diff on failure (expected vs actual), which is why you never need <code>assertEqual</code> style methods. This is the single biggest ergonomic win over unittest.</li>\n      <li><strong>Fixtures are dependency injection:</strong> a <code>@pytest.fixture</code> function provides reusable setup (a database connection, a temp file, sample data). Tests receive it by naming it as a parameter \u2014 pytest matches the name and injects the return value. Fixtures can depend on other fixtures, and scope (function/module/session) controls how often they rebuild. This replaces setUp/tearDown with something composable.</li>\n      <li><strong>Parametrize runs one test across many inputs:</strong> <code>@pytest.mark.parametrize(\"input,expected\", [...])</code> runs the same test body once per tuple, each reported separately. This is how you test edge cases (empty, negative, boundary) without copy-pasting the test. A failure tells you exactly which input broke.</li>\n      <li><strong>Mocking \u2014 patch where it's used, not where it's defined:</strong> <code>patch</code> replaces a dependency with a MagicMock during a test so you don't hit real APIs or databases. The critical rule: patch the name in the module that <em>imports</em> it, not the module that defines it \u2014 <code>patch('myapp.service.requests')</code>, not <code>patch('requests')</code>. Getting this wrong is the #1 mocking bug and the mock silently does nothing.</li>\n      <li><strong>Profiling before optimising:</strong> <code>cProfile</code> instruments the whole program and reports where time is actually spent \u2014 almost always somewhere you didn't expect. Optimising without profiling first is guessing. Use <code>pstats</code> to sort by cumulative time and find the real bottleneck before touching any code.</li>\n      <li><strong>Debugging with breakpoint():</strong> <code>breakpoint()</code> drops into pdb at that line. Core commands: <code>n</code> (next line), <code>s</code> (step into call), <code>c</code> (continue), <code>p var</code> (print), <code>l</code> (list surrounding code). Far faster than scattering print statements, and you can inspect any variable in scope interactively.</li>\n      <li><strong>Logging levels and logger.exception():</strong> DEBUG &lt; INFO &lt; WARNING &lt; ERROR &lt; CRITICAL \u2014 set the threshold at config time and everything below it is suppressed. Inside an except block, <code>logger.exception(\"msg\")</code> logs at ERROR level and automatically attaches the full traceback \u2014 use it instead of <code>logger.error(str(e))</code>, which loses the stack trace.</li>\n    </ol>\n  </div>\n\n<h2 id=\"py-testing\"><span class=\"num\">16</span>Testing & Debugging</h2>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 pytest</span>\n    <p>Python's standard testing framework. Any function whose name starts with <code>test_</code> in any file starting with <code>test_</code> is automatically discovered and run. Uses plain <code>assert</code> statements \u2014 pytest rewrites them to show detailed diffs on failure rather than just \"AssertionError\". Three core features: <strong>fixtures</strong> (reusable setup injected by parameter name), <strong>parametrize</strong> (run one test with many inputs), <strong>raises</strong> (assert an exception is raised).</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Why testing feels like overhead but isn't</span>\n    <p>A production ML pipeline has 15 steps. Step 12 fails silently \u2014 it returns wrong data instead of an error. Steps 13\u201315 run fine on the wrong data. The model retrains on corrupted features. Three weeks of training later, model quality drops. You have no idea why.<br><br>\n    A unit test on step 12 catches this in 50 milliseconds. The argument \"I don't have time to write tests\" is the argument \"I have time for two weeks of debugging later, just not now.\"</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">patch where it's USED, not where it's defined \u2014 the most common mock mistake</span>\n    <p>You want to mock <code>requests.get</code>. It's defined in the <code>requests</code> library. But your code does <code>from requests import get</code> in <code>mymodule.py</code>. Patching <code>requests.get</code> does nothing \u2014 your module already has its own reference to the function. You must patch <code>mymodule.get</code> \u2014 where the name is actually used. The rule: patch the name in the namespace where your code under test looks it up.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <h3>Profiling \u2014 find the bottleneck before optimising</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout intu\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Analogy \u2014 a doctor diagnosing before prescribing</span>\n    <p>A doctor does not prescribe medication based on a guess. They run tests, get results, find the actual cause, then treat it. Optimising code without profiling is prescribing without diagnosing. You guess the bottleneck (usually wrong), spend time fixing it, and the program is still slow because the real problem was somewhere else entirely. Profile first. The data tells you what to fix.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Profiling</span>\n    <p>Measuring where a program spends its time. <code>cProfile</code> instruments every function call and reports: how many times each function was called, total time spent in it, and cumulative time including sub-calls. <code>pstats</code> sorts and filters the output. <code>timeit</code> times a single expression across many repetitions for micro-benchmarking. Rule: always profile before optimising. The bottleneck is almost never where you think it is.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">The optimisation order that actually works</span>\n    <p>Wrong order: write code \u2192 notice it's slow \u2192 optimise the part that looks slow \u2192 still slow \u2192 optimise another part \u2192 spent a week on the wrong thing.<br>\n    Right order: write code \u2192 make it correct (tests pass) \u2192 profile \u2192 find the actual bottleneck (it's almost always I/O or a nested loop you didn't notice) \u2192 optimise only that \u2192 re-profile to confirm. \"Make it work, make it right, make it fast\" \u2014 in that order, not the other.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <h3>Logging \u2014 structured observability</h3>\n\n  <div class=\"callout def\">\n    <span class=\"label\">Definition \u2014 Python Logging</span>\n    <p>The standard library module for emitting structured diagnostic messages. Has five severity levels: <code>DEBUG</code> (verbose development info) \u2192 <code>INFO</code> (normal operation) \u2192 <code>WARNING</code> (something unexpected but handled) \u2192 <code>ERROR</code> (something failed) \u2192 <code>CRITICAL</code> (system may not recover). Level is set at configuration time \u2014 below the threshold, messages are discarded with near-zero cost. <code>logger.exception()</code> logs at ERROR level and automatically appends the full traceback.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"callout trap\">\n    <span class=\"label\">print() vs logging \u2014 why print() in production is wrong</span>\n    <p><code>print()</code> has no level, no timestamp, no module name, no way to filter by severity, and no way to route to a file. When your production pipeline fails at 3am, you have a wall of undifferentiated print output with no timestamps and no context.<br>\n    Logging gives you: timestamp, severity, module name, line number, and the ability to set a threshold (only show WARNING and above in production, DEBUG in development). One config change toggles verbosity. Zero code changes needed.</p>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># pytest \u2014 the standard Python testing framework</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># File: test_model.py (pytest finds files starting with test_)</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pytest\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> myproject.model <span class=\"k\">import</span> LinearModel\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Basic test \u2014 function starting with test_</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_predict_shape</span>():\n    model = LinearModel(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">10</span>, output_dim=<span class=\"y\">3</span>)\n    output = model.predict([[<span class=\"y\">1</span>]*<span class=\"y\">10</span>])\n    assert output.shape == (<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">3</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># pytest shows diff on failure</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># pytest.raises \u2014 test exceptions</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_invalid_input</span>():\n    model = LinearModel(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> pytest.raises(ValueError, match=<span class=\"g\">\"expected 10 features\"</span>):\n        model.predict([[<span class=\"y\">1</span>, <span class=\"y\">2</span>]])   <span class=\"c\"># wrong shape \u2014 should raise ValueError</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Parameterized tests \u2014 run same test with multiple inputs</span>\n<span class=\"o\">@pytest.mark.parametrize</span>(<span class=\"g\">\"input,expected\"</span>, [\n    ([<span class=\"y\">0</span>]*<span class=\"y\">10</span>, [<span class=\"y\">0</span>]*<span class=\"y\">3</span>),\n    ([<span class=\"y\">1</span>]*<span class=\"y\">10</span>, [<span class=\"y\">1</span>]*<span class=\"y\">3</span>),\n])\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_predict_values</span>(input, expected):\n    model = LinearModel.identity(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\n    assert model.predict([input]) == [expected]\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Fixtures \u2014 reusable setup</span>\n<span class=\"o\">@pytest.fixture</span>\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">trained_model</span>():\n    model = LinearModel(input_dim=<span class=\"y\">10</span>)\n    model.fit(training_data)\n    <span class=\"k\">return</span> model                   <span class=\"c\"># every test that needs it gets a fresh one</span>\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_with_fixture</span>(trained_model):\n    assert trained_model.accuracy > <span class=\"y\">0.8</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># Mocking \u2014 replace external dependencies</span>\n<span class=\"k\">from</span> unittest.mock <span class=\"k\">import</span> patch, MagicMock\n\n<span class=\"k\">def</span> <span class=\"o\">test_api_call</span>():\n    <span class=\"k\">with</span> patch(<span class=\"g\">\"myproject.client.requests.get\"</span>) <span class=\"k\">as</span> mock_get:\n        mock_get.return_value.json.return_value = {<span class=\"g\">\"status\"</span>: <span class=\"g\">\"ok\"</span>}\n        result = call_api(<span class=\"g\">\"http://api.example.com\"</span>)\n        assert result == {<span class=\"g\">\"status\"</span>: <span class=\"g\">\"ok\"</span>}\n        mock_get.assert_called_once_with(<span class=\"g\">\"http://api.example.com\"</span>)</div>\n\n  <div class=\"fx\"><span class=\"c\"># Profiling \u2014 find where time is spent</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> cProfile, pstats\n\n<span class=\"k\">with</span> cProfile.Profile() <span class=\"k\">as</span> pr:\n    my_slow_function()\n\nstats = pstats.Stats(pr)\nstats.sort_stats(<span class=\"g\">\"cumulative\"</span>)\nstats.print_stats(<span class=\"y\">10</span>)   <span class=\"c\"># top 10 time-consuming functions\n\n# timeit \u2014 benchmark small snippets</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> timeit\ntimeit.timeit(<span class=\"g\">\"[x**2 for x in range(1000)]\"</span>, number=<span class=\"y\">1000</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># run 1000 times, return total\n\n# pdb \u2014 interactive debugger</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> pdb\npdb.set_trace()    <span class=\"c\"># drops into debugger at this line</span>\n<span class=\"c\"># Commands: n(ext), s(tep), c(ontinue), l(ist), p variable, q(uit)</span>\n\n<span class=\"c\"># breakpoint() \u2014 Python 3.7+ cleaner syntax</span>\nbreakpoint()       <span class=\"c\"># same as pdb.set_trace() but respects PYTHONBREAKPOINT env var\n\n# Logging \u2014 structured observability for production</span>\n<span class=\"k\">import</span> logging\n\nlogging.basicConfig(\n    level=logging.DEBUG,\n    format=<span class=\"g\">'%(asctime)s %(name)s %(levelname)s %(message)s'</span>,\n    handlers=[\n        logging.StreamHandler(),               <span class=\"c\"># stdout</span>\n        logging.FileHandler(<span class=\"g\">\"app.log\"</span>),       <span class=\"c\"># file</span>\n    ]\n)\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\nlogger.debug(<span class=\"g\">\"debugging detail\"</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># dev only</span>\nlogger.info(<span class=\"g\">\"model loaded\"</span>)          <span class=\"c\"># normal operations</span>\nlogger.warning(<span class=\"g\">\"GPU memory low\"</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># something unexpected</span>\nlogger.error(<span class=\"g\">\"prediction failed\"</span>)    <span class=\"c\"># error, but continuing</span>\nlogger.critical(<span class=\"g\">\"database down\"</span>)     <span class=\"c\"># entire system affected</span>\nlogger.exception(<span class=\"g\">\"unhandled error\"</span>)  <span class=\"c\"># error + full traceback</span></div>\n\n  <!-- Q&A -->\n  <h2 id=\"py-qa\"><span class=\"num\">17</span>Interview Q&A</h2>\n  <div class=\"qa-head\"><h3>Answer before revealing</h3><button class=\"reveal-all\" id=\"revealAll\">Reveal all</button></div>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the difference between is and ==?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">== checks value equality \u2014 do the two objects have the same value? is checks object identity \u2014 are the two variables pointing to the exact same object in memory (same id()). Example: a = [1,2]; b = [1,2]; a == b is True (same values) but a is b is False (different list objects). Important: always use is for None checks (a is None, not a == None) because == calls __eq__ which can be overridden.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Mutable vs immutable \u2014 give examples and explain why it matters.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Mutable: list, dict, set, bytearray \u2014 can be changed after creation. Immutable: int, float, str, tuple, frozenset \u2014 every \"change\" creates a new object. Matters because: (1) mutable objects passed to functions can be modified in place, causing unexpected side effects. (2) Only hashable (immutable) objects can be dict keys or set elements. (3) Aliasing bug: b = a creates a second reference to the same mutable object \u2014 modifying through a also changes b.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is the GIL and when does it matter?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">The Global Interpreter Lock is a mutex in CPython that prevents multiple threads from executing Python bytecode simultaneously. Only one thread runs at a time. For CPU-bound tasks (computation, ML training), threads provide no speedup \u2014 use multiprocessing instead. For I/O-bound tasks (API calls, file reads, network), the GIL is released while waiting for I/O, so threads do help. Alternatively, use asyncio for I/O-bound work with a single thread.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>How does a generator save memory compared to a list?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">A list computes and stores all values upfront in memory. A generator computes values lazily \u2014 one at a time, only when next() is called. For [x**2 for x in range(1_000_000)], the list allocates ~8MB immediately. The equivalent generator (x**2 for x in range(1_000_000)) uses ~120 bytes \u2014 just enough to store the current state. Critical for ML: batch generators process large datasets without loading them entirely into memory.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is a decorator and how do you implement one?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">A decorator is a function that takes a function and returns a modified function. @timer above a function is syntactic sugar for func = timer(func). Implementation: the decorator defines an inner wrapper function that adds behaviour before/after calling the original function, then returns the wrapper. Always use @functools.wraps(func) on the wrapper to preserve the original function's __name__ and __doc__ attributes.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>When would you use multiprocessing vs threading vs asyncio?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Threading: I/O-bound tasks where you want multiple concurrent operations \u2014 API calls, file reads, DB queries. GIL is released during I/O so threads make real progress in parallel. Multiprocessing: CPU-bound tasks \u2014 data transformation, parallel ML training, heavy computation. Each process has its own Python interpreter and GIL, so true parallelism is achieved. Asyncio: I/O-bound tasks where you control all the code and want maximum efficiency with minimal overhead. Single thread, no locking needed, most efficient for high-concurrency I/O like web servers.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>Explain SOLID principles briefly.</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Single Responsibility: one class, one reason to change. Open/Closed: open for extension (add subclass), closed for modification (don't change existing code). Liskov Substitution: subclass can replace parent without breaking code \u2014 if Bird has fly(), and Penguin(Bird) overrides fly() to raise NotImplementedError, that violates LSP. Interface Segregation: don't force classes to implement methods they don't use \u2014 split large interfaces. Dependency Inversion: depend on abstractions (ABC/interfaces), not concrete implementations. Allows easy swapping of components.</div></details>\n\n  <details class=\"qa\"><summary><span class=\"qmark\">Q</span>What is shallow copy vs deep copy?</summary><div class=\"qa-body\">Shallow copy (list.copy(), copy.copy(), list slicing): creates a new container but the elements inside are the same objects. So if the list contains mutable objects (like nested lists), those inner objects are shared. Modifying a nested list in the copy also modifies the original. Deep copy (copy.deepcopy()): recursively copies everything \u2014 new container AND new copies of all nested objects. No sharing. Use deep copy when you have nested mutable structures and need true independence between original and copy.</div></details>\n</main>\n\n\n</main>",
});